{:task "risk-analysis", :generated-tree-raw [:sequence [:chunk-document {:from :yyj_rfp, :size 15000, :into :rfp_chunks}] [:map-each {:from :rfp_chunks, :as :chunk, :into :chunk_analyses, :max-concurrency 5} [:llm {:instruction "Analyze this section of the RFP for Parking Management Services. \n                         Identify and evaluate:\n                         1. OBLIGATIONS: Mandatory compliance, operational requirements, and financial commitments.\n                         2. PENALTIES: Specific triggers for fines, liquidated damages, or termination.\n                         3. RISKS: Evaluate the difficulty of meeting these obligations and the severity of impact if failed (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW).\n                         Focus on hidden liabilities and operational complexities. Provide an analytical summary of these points for this section.", :reads [:chunk], :writes [:analysis]}]] [:aggregate {:from :chunk_analyses, :writes [:aggregated_risk_data]}] [:llm {:instruction "Consolidate the section-by-section analyses into a final comprehensive report.\n                        Provide the following sections:\n                        1. Obligations: A structured list categorized by Mandatory, Compliance, Operational, and Financial.\n                        2. Penalties: A summary of all non-compliance consequences, including termination rights and financial penalties.\n                        3. Risk-Matrix: Map key obligations to their Risk Level (High/Medium/Low) based on difficulty and consequence.\n                        4. Executive Summary: A high-level synthesis of major concerns and strategic recommendations for the bidder.", :reads [:aggregated_risk_data], :writes [:obligations :penalties :risk-matrix :executive-summary]}] [:final {:keys [:obligations :penalties :risk-matrix :executive-summary]}]], :total-chars 280140, :duration-ms 156522, :documents {:yyj_rfp {:chars 280140}}, :task-name "Risk & Obligation Analysis", :usage {:prompt-tokens 128453, :completion-tokens 23659, :total-tokens 152112}, :status :success, :outputs {:penalties "*   **High-Usury Interest:** Late remittances of gross revenue incur interest at **2% per month (26.824% per annum)**, compounded monthly.\n*   **Audit Cost Shifting:** If a VAA audit reveals a revenue understatement of **1% or more**, the Contractor must pay the full cost of the audit plus interest and face potential termination.\n*   **Revenue Liability (Theft):** The definition of \"Gross Revenue\" include monies lost to **theft, employee dishonesty, or defalcation**. The Contractor is an insurer for VAA's revenue.\n*   **Default via LC:** VAA may draw the entire 5% LC if a renewal is not provided 3 weeks before expiry. Replenishment of a drawn LC is required within 15 days.\n*   **Termination for Labor Disruption:** VAA reserves the right to terminate if a labor disruption/strike exceeds 7 consecutive days.\n*   **Personal Debt for Collections:** Failure to document the 3-step collection process results in the Contractor assuming **personal liability** for uncollected fees.", :chunk_analyses [{:analysis "### **Analytical Summary of Parking Management Services RFP (Pages 1-7)**\n\n#### **1. OBLIGATIONS**\n*   **Operational Staffing:** Mandatory local office presence within two months of award. Must provide a qualified on-site manager and staff \"lot attendant\" booths for a minimum of **20 hours per day, 7 days a week**.\n*   **Program Development:** The Operator is explicitly required to \"develop and implement\" a **Curb Management Program** to manage traffic flow at terminal frontages and commercial lanes.\n*   **Maintenance:** Mandatory responsibility for **ice control and snow removal** in specific areas (Appendix C) and routine trash pickup/patrolling.\n*   **Financial Reporting/Revenue:** Responsible for collecting and accounting for all revenue (cash, credit, debit) and managing Sales Tax at the retailer level.\n*   **Social Responsibility:** Proponents are expected to identify opportunities for **Indigenous business engagement**, training, and employment.\n\n#### **2. PENALTIES**\n*   **Technical Non-Compliance:** The Authority reserves the right to reject proposals for minor or technical non-compliance (Section 1.5).\n*   **Service Standards:** Failure to meet \"Quality Standards\" (Schedule 8) or \"key performance standards\" (Section 1.6) may trigger contractual penalties, though specific dollar-amount fines are located in the later sections/Appendix H (Draft Contract).\n*   **Termination:** While specific \"triggers\" are in the draft contract (Appendix H), the overview establishes that the 2-year renewal option is at the **\"sole discretion of the Authority,\"** providing a non-renewal penalty for sub-par performance.\n\n#### **3. RISKS**\n*   **Terminal Expansion Project (HIGH):** The RFP notes a forthcoming expansion that is \"expected to impact parking,\" but the specifics are \"uncertain.\" This creates a high risk for the Operator regarding revenue fluctuations, displaced spaces, and changing traffic patterns that may not be fully priced into the five-year term.\n*   **Curb Management Complexity (MEDIUM):** Developing a Curb Management Program from scratch requires balancing enforcement with customer service; poor execution here directly impacts the Authority's primary \"first impression\" metric.\n*   **Staffing & Local Presence (MEDIUM):** The mandate for a local office and 20-hour staffing in a potentially tight labor market (Victoria, BC) poses operational cost risks.\n*   **Revenue Collection (MEDIUM):** As the \"Operator\" handles all payment forms, they bear the liability for audit discrepancies and the security of financial transactions.\n\n#### **Analytical Conclusion**\nThis RFP transitions the provider from a simple staffing agency to a comprehensive \"Operator\" responsible for strategic program development (Curb Management) and environmental maintenance (Snow/Ice). The primary hidden liability lies in Section 1.2 regarding the **Terminal Expansion Project**; the lack of certainty regarding its impact means the Proponent must build flexibility into their financial model to account for potential lot closures or reduced capacity during the 5-year term."} {:analysis "### 1. OBLIGATIONS\n*   **Operational Coverage:** Mandatory staffing of terminal frontage and commercial lanes for at least 15.5 hours daily, 7 days a week.\n*   **Labor Standards:** Must pay above BC provincial minimum wage plus benefits; staff must be fluent in English and legally eligible to work in Canada.\n*   **Training & Compliance:** Extensive mandatory training (WorldHost Customer Service, Sensitivity, 12 hours OJT, technical, and VAA-specific security/accessibility programs) at the Proponent's expense. Records must be audit-ready for the CTA.\n*   **Financial Management:** \n    *   Full responsibility for invoicing/collection for Employee, Commuter, and Monthly permit programs (previously managed by VAA).\n    *   Weekly bank deposits of collected revenue.\n    *   Remittance of all revenue/taxes to VAA by the 5th business day of the following month.\n*   **Marketing & Innovation:** Mandatory 0.5% budget of public parking revenues for marketing. Expectation to fund infrastructure for new \"innovative\" services (e.g., Valets) with later charge-backs.\n*   **Health & Safety:** Maintain a WorkSafe BC compliant OH&S program at the Proponent’s own expense.\n\n### 2. PENALTIES\n*   **Audit Rights:** The Authority reserves the right to audit staff records, performance, customer service levels, and financial transactions at *any time* without prior notification.\n*   **Transition Costs:** Any costs related to establishing operations or transitioning are the sole responsibility of the Proponent; failure to account for these is a financial loss.\n*   **Liability:** The Proponent accepts full responsibility for all collected revenues and any property damage or injury occurring within their operational areas.\n\n### 3. RISKS\n*   **Financial Liability (HIGH):** The Proponent is responsible for the \"security of all revenues.\" Any theft, shortfalls, or invoicing errors in the Employee/Commuter programs—which are now the Proponent's responsibility to collect—represent a direct bottom-line risk.\n*   **Staffing & Retention (HIGH):** Requirement to pay above minimum wage in a likely competitive labor market, combined with the need to provide \"additional trained staff\" for \"unpredictable\" peak periods, creates significant margin pressure. \n*   **Operational Complexity (MEDIUM):** Transitioning existing VAA programs (Employee/Commuter parking) into the Proponent’s scope involves significant data migration and billing setup risks.\n*   **Unfunded Mandates (MEDIUM):** The requirement to implement \"future training programs\" and \"internet-based marketing\" at the Proponent's expense/effort creates \"scope creep\" potential.\n*   **Infrastructure Spend (MEDIUM):** While \"charged back,\" the initial capital outlay for new services (Valet/Shuttles) is borne by the Proponent, impacting cash flow.\n\n### Analytical Summary\nThe section shifts substantial administrative and financial weight from the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) to the Contractor, specifically regarding the Management of Employee/Permit programs. The most significant hidden liability is the Proponent's responsibility for the **security and collection of revenues**; if a monthly permit holder fails to pay or funds are lost/stolen, the Proponent likely carries that burden. Furthermore, the 15.5-hour daily staffing requirement combined with the \"unpredictable\" need for extra staff makes labor cost management the primary operational challenge."} {:analysis "### 1. OBLIGATIONS\n*   **Mandatory Site Attendance:** Participation in the pre-bid meeting/site tour (Feb 27, 2025) is a prerequisite for bidding. Attendees must bring government ID and CSA-certified high-visibility vests.\n*   **Due Diligence:** Section 2.6 shifts the entire burden of knowledge onto the Proponent. By submitting, the Proponent represents they have \"thoroughly examined\" the site, equipment, labor market, and all applicable laws/regulations.\n*   **Submission Formatting:** Must provide one (1) hard copy and one (1) digital copy (USB). No email or hand-written submissions.\n*   **Validity Period:** Proposals must remain valid and irrevocable for sixty (60) days post-closing.\n*   **Disclosure:** Proponents must disclose any relationships with Authority employees/directors and any partnerships or sub-contracting arrangements.\n\n### 2. PENALTIES\n*   **Exclusion from Bidding:** Failure to submit the \"Receipt Confirmation Form\" (Schedule 1) or failure to attend the mandatory site tour results in immediate exclusion.\n*   **Rejection of Late Bids:** Strict deadline of March 31, 2025, 2:00 PM PST; the Authority’s time stamp is final.\n*   **Termination for Non-Disclosure:** Under Section 2.17, false or insufficient disclosure of interests/relationships is grounds for immediate contract termination without liability or notice.\n*   **Disqualification for Non-Compliance:** Qualifying conditions or failure to follow instructions may lead to immediate disqualification.\n\n### 3. RISKS\n*   **Operational Complexity (MEDIUM):** The requirement to assess the \"equipment and materials\" and \"labor market\" prior to bidding implies the Proponent must understand the current technical state of the airport's parking infrastructure without a guarantee of perfectly accurate data provided by the Authority.\n*   **Hidden Liabilities (HIGH):** \n    *   **Section 2.5/2.14 (Oral Representations):** Proponents are strictly prohibited from relying on any oral communication. Only written addenda are binding. Any misunderstanding of the RFP is the \"sole responsibility\" of the Proponent.\n    *   **Section 2.9 (No Cost Recovery):** All costs for site visits, travel, and proposal preparation are non-reimbursable, even if the RFP is canceled.\n    *   **Section 2.18 (Reserved Rights):** The Authority has broad discretion to negotiate with multiple Proponents concurrently, waive irregularities, or cancel the RFP entirely without liability.\n*   **Regulatory Risk (MEDIUM):** The Proponent warrants they are knowledgeable of all B.C. labor laws and standards. Failure to account for these in the financial bid (Schedule 5) will not be grounds for price adjustments later.\n\n### Analytical Summary\nThis section establishes a \"Buyer Beware\" framework. It heavily protects the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) from liability regarding the accuracy of information or the costs of bidding. The most critical operational risk is the **Mandatory Attendance** and the **Full Disclosure** requirement; any oversight in revealing a professional relationship could result in a \"kill switch\" termination of a future contract. Proponents should ensure their site visit is exhaustive, as the RFP explicitly states that submission constitutes acceptance of the site condition \"as-is.\""} {:analysis "### **Analytical Summary: Parking Management Services RFP**\n\n#### **1. OBLIGATIONS: Mandatory Compliance & Operations**\n*   **Operational Continuity:** The successful proponent must provide **continuous staffing** of parking facilities on a full-time basis, aligned with all arriving and departing flights (regardless of delays), effectively covering all hours except the current terminal closure window (01:00 am – 03:30 am).\n*   **Regulatory Adherence:** Mandatory compliance with federal, provincial, and local laws, specifically citing **WorkSafe BC**, electrical/building codes, and various governmental jurisdictions.\n*   **Licensing:** The proponent is solely responsible for obtaining and maintaining all necessary permits and licenses required for airport operations.\n*   **Cooperation:** Proponents must consent to and cooperate with deep-dive investigations into their financial capability, business experience, and legal history (Section 2.23).\n*   **Contractual Timelines:** A contract must be finalized within **30 business days** of award notification, or the proponent risks forfeiture of the opportunity.\n\n#### **2. PENALTIES: Triggers for Loss & Liability**\n*   **Invalidation:** Any electronic alteration of the RFP document (except for filling requested fields) results in immediate invalidation of the proposal.\n*   **Forfeiture of Rights:** Failure to conclude negotiations within the 30-day window allows the Authority to cancel the award and move to the next candidate without compensation.\n*   **Negotiation Termination:** The Authority reserves the right to terminate negotiations at any time without paying any compensation for the proponent's costs or lost profits.\n*   **Total Liability Waiver:** The proponent explicitly waives any right to claim damages for proposal preparation costs or loss of anticipated profits if no contract is signed.\n\n#### **3. RISKS: Evaluation of Difficulty and Impact**\n*   **Exclusivity Risk (HIGH):** Section 3.8 explicitly states the Authority **will not grant exclusivity**. The Authority may enter into other contracts for similar services at any time. This creates a high risk of revenue dilution and competitive pressure within the same facility.\n*   **Open-Ended Contract Terms (MEDIUM/HIGH):** The Authority reserves the right to \"negotiate, modify, and/or add any contract terms\" during the award phase. This allows for \"scope creep\" or the addition of more onerous terms after the proponent has already committed to their financial bid.\n*   **Information Accuracy (MEDIUM):** The \"As-Is\" disclaimer (Section 2.25) and the waiver regarding electronic transmission accuracy place the risk of data errors entirely on the proponent. Bidders must perform significant due diligence as the Authority disclaims responsibility for the data provided in the RFP.\n*   **Financial Vetting (MEDIUM):** Requirements for bank references and disclosure of past litigation/bankruptcies create a high barrier for proponents with irregular financial histories or previous legal disputes.\n\n### **Hidden Liabilities & Complexities**\n*   **The \"Shadow\" Contract:** While Appendix H provides a template, the RFP grants the Authority broad power to change the contract post-bid.\n*   **Flight-Linked Staffing:** Because staffing is tied to flight schedules, operational costs are volatile. If flight schedules expand or delays occur, the proponent's labor costs will increase without a guaranteed mechanism for fee adjustment in this section.\n*   **Investigation Consent:** Proponents are essentially signing a \"blank check\" for the Authority to investigate their private business practices and financial records."} {:analysis "### 1. OBLIGATIONS\n*   **Financial Bonding:** Must provide an Irrevocable Letter of Credit equal to 5% of the total Fixed Management Fee for the Initial Term.\n*   **Insurance & Compliance:** Mandatory evidence of insurability and proof of good standing with WorkSafe BC. Successful proponent must obtain a Municipal Business License.\n*   **Operational Scope:** Requirement to manage ice control, snow removal, and a seasonal shuttle service (Dec 22 – Jan 15, 04:00 to 01:00) within the Fixed Management Fee.\n*   **Revenue Management:** Proponents must take over the invoicing and payment management for employee, commuter, and monthly permits (previously handled by VAA).\n*   **Marketing Commitment:** Mandatory allocation of **0.5% of public parking revenue** toward marketing strategies.\n*   **Reporting:** Requirement to provide statistical reporting (occupancy/passage) and maintain a \"sophisticated\" financial reporting system with separate income streams.\n*   **Transition:** Proponents are responsible for all startup/transition costs; these cannot be billed back to the Authority.\n\n### 2. PENALTIES\n*   **Audit Rights:** The VAA maintains a strict right of audit. Discrepancies in financial reporting or internal controls are implied triggers for contractual default.\n*   **Bond Forfeiture:** While not explicitly detailed in the \"trigger\" sense in this chunk, the requirement for a Letter of Credit implies it serves as security against non-performance.\n*   **Non-Compliance Rejection:** Failure to provide WorkSafe BC proof before June 1, 2025, or failure to meet insurance requirements will prevent contract execution.\n\n### 3. RISKS\n*   **Scope Creep (HIGH):** The Fixed Management Fee is inclusive of unpredictable costs like **ice control and snow removal**. A severe winter could lead to significant financial loss as these costs cannot be passed to the Authority.\n*   **Regulatory Complexity (MEDIUM):** Requirement to describe plans to meet the **Official Languages Act**, implying a bilingual service standard that may increase recruitment costs and operational complexity.\n*   **Technological Liability (MEDIUM):** Transitioning existing equipment (Skidata/Flowbird) and implementing new statistical/financial reporting systems carries the risk of data gaps or integration failures during the handover of permit programs.\n*   **Underestimation of Transition (MEDIUM):** The clause stating all startup costs are the \"sole responsibility of the successful Proponent\" places the financial risk of a botched or complex handover entirely on the contractor.\n*   **Marketing Spend Risk (LOW):** While 0.5% is a fixed obligation, it is tied to revenue, meaning fluctuations in airport traffic directly affect the required marketing budget.\n\n### Analytical Summary\nThis section shifts significant financial and weather-related risks onto the operator by bundling variable-cost services (snow/ice/shuttle) into a **Fixed Management Fee**. The requirement for the operator to take over permit invoicing and payment management introduces a new layer of administrative and fiduciary responsibility compared to previous contracts. Proponents should be particularly wary of the \"sophisticated financial reporting\" and \"Official Languages Act\" requirements, which may necessitate specialized staff or software beyond standard parking operations."} {:analysis "### 1. OBLIGATIONS: Mandatory Compliance, Operational Requirements, and Financial Commitments\n*   **Equipment Monitoring & Reporting:** While VAA (Victoria Airport Authority) is responsible for repairs and maintenance of parking equipment, the Contractor has a mandatory obligation to **monitor all equipment** and **report any observed conditions** requiring intervention.\n*   **Facility Scope:** Management extends across several distinct areas totaling over 90,000m², including:\n    *   Short-Term (Blue Lot)\n    *   Long-Term Lot 1 (Green Lot)\n    *   Long-Term Lot 2 (Orange Lot)\n    *   Employee Lot (Yellow Lot)\n    *   Overflow Lots (Brown, Purple, Red)\n*   **Operational Requirements:** The Contractor must operate a mix of multi-vendor technology from **SKIDATA** (Long-term/Employee) and **FLOWBIRD** (Short-term), including Hesion LPR (License Plate Recognition) and Moneris payment processing.\n*   **Administrative/Reporting:** The Contractor is obligated to generate and likely verify complex occupancy and transaction reports (as evidenced by Appendices D and E), tracking hourly entrances, exits, and occupancy vs. passenger counts.\n\n### 2. PENALTIES: Specific Triggers for Fines or Termination\n*   **Reporting Failures:** While specific dollar amounts for fines are not in this chunk, the emphasis on the \"Contractor is responsible for monitoring... and reporting\" implies that failure to notify VAA of equipment downtime could lead to liability for lost revenue.\n*   **Management Performance:** The detailed sample reports (Appendix E) suggest that the Contractor will be held to performance metrics based on \"Actual Counts\" vs. \"System Counts.\" Discrepancies in these audits often trigger financial reconciliation requirements or penalties in parking contracts.\n\n### 3. RISKS: Difficulty and Severity\n*   **Operational Complexity (HIGH):** The Contractor must manage a \"fragmented\" technology stack. Operating two different major systems (Skidata and Flowbird) simultaneously increases the training burden on staff and the risk of reporting errors or sync issues between lots.\n*   **Asset Liability (MEDIUM):** VAA provides equipment with a Net Book Value (NBV) of ~$1.54M. Although VAA handles repairs, the Contractor's \"monitoring\" role is a hidden liability; if a gate or LPR camera is damaged or malfunctioning and the Contractor fails to report it promptly, they may be held responsible for the resulting revenue leakage.\n*   **Winter Operations (MEDIUM/HIGH):** The included \"Snow Removal and Ice Control\" map and the requirement for \"T. Albert\" levels of coordination suggest the Contractor may have significant mobilization obligations during weather events. Failure to keep lots clear leads to high-severity safety risks and revenue loss.\n*   **LPR Accuracy (MEDIUM):** The equipment list shows LPR (License Plate Recognition) at every entry/exit. If LPR accuracy drops, it creates significant manual work for staff in \"lost ticket\" situations or dispute resolution, impacting customer satisfaction and throughput.\n\n### Analytical Summary\nThe technical environment is complex, requiring a Contractor proficient in **dual-vendor systems** and **LPR technology**. A significant \"hidden\" liability lies in the **reporting interface**: VAA maintains the hardware, but the Contractor owns the \"eyes and ears\" responsibility. If the system fails to record a transaction and the Contractor didn't report the hardware fault, the financial loss could be shifted to the Contractor. Prospective bidders should verify the \"hand-off\" protocol for maintenance requests to ensure they are not blamed for the aging of equipment (Skidata installed 2020) or Flowbird integration issues."} {:analysis "### **Analytical Summary: Appendix F - Passenger Activity and Market Information**\n\nThis section provides the statistical foundation upon which the Parking Management Services contract is predicated. It outlines historical data, growth forecasts, and passenger behavioral demographics.\n\n#### **1. OBLIGATIONS: Mandatory Compliance & Operational Requirements**\n*   **Capacity Management:** Total parking occupancy fluctuated near ~1,200 vehicles during peak Wednesday data. The Operator must manage capacity across Lot 1 and Lot 2 to accommodate a projected growth from **1.87M (2024)** to **2.22M (2028)** annual passengers.\n*   **Operational Staffing Alignment:** Resource allocation must mirror the \"Estimated Passengers by Hour\" charts. Peak entry activity occurs between **03:00 and 10:00**, while peak exit activity is heavily weighted toward the evening and late-night hours (**21:00 to 00:00**).\n*   **Seasonal Scalability:** Operations must scale for significant seasonality, with peak requirements in **August** and reduced needs in **February**.\n*   **Market Intelligence:** Proponents are obligated to perform their own due diligence; the RFP explicitly notes that \"Proponents should interpret the passenger information with their own expectations.\"\n\n#### **2. PENALTIES: Specific Triggers**\n*   **Data Accuracy Disclaimer:** The Authority provides a comprehensive **Disclaimer of Liability**. There are no explicit financial \"penalties\" in this section, but the risk of financial loss due to reliance on inaccurate forecasts rests solely on the Proponent.\n*   **Under-Performance Risk:** While not listed as a fine, failure to adapt to the 6.2%–6.6% near-term growth rates could lead to operational failure (gridlock), which typically triggers \"Failure to Perform\" clauses elsewhere in the RFP.\n\n#### **3. RISKS: Difficulty and Impact**\n*   **Forecasting Accuracy (HIGH):** The Authority assumes no responsibility for deviations from forecasts. If the Operator bids based on these numbers and traffic underperforms (or exceeds capacity), the Operator bears the financial/operational burden.\n*   **Labor/Staffing Complexity (MEDIUM):** The hourly entry/exit data shows a \"double peak\" (early morning and late night). This creates split-shift complexities or high overtime costs to ensure adequate coverage during disjointed peak windows.\n*   **Revenue Leakage/Captive Market Change (HIGH):** 2024 ASQ results show that **21%** of passengers use a private car to travel to the airport, but only **40%** of those surveyed \"used parking.\" This indicates a high \"drop-off\" rate (**36%**) and a potential vulnerability to ridesharing (**6%**) and taxis (**15%**). Any increase in rideshare adoption directly threatens the Proponent’s revenue model if the contract is performance or percentage-based.\n*   **Infrastructure Stress (MEDIUM):** With 2028 forecasts reaching over 2.2M passengers, current parking footprints (Lot 1/Lot 2) may reach physical saturation, requiring the Operator to manage extreme congestion or implement valet/overflow protocols.\n\n### **Hidden Liabilities & Operational Complexities**\n*   **The \"Gap\" in Utilization:** There is a discrepancy between the \"10.29% Passengers Parking\" figure in the raw data and the \"40% used parking\" in the ASQ annual report. This suggests ASQ data may include short-term/metered use, whereas the operational data tracks long-term occupancy. Miscalculating this \"intent to park\" ratio is the primary financial risk for the Proponent.\n*   **International Growth:** International travel grew **123.7%** in 2024. International passengers typically have longer dwell times (higher revenue per stall) compared to domestic. The Operator must monitor this mix closely, as it significantly impacts revenue yield per space."} {:analysis "### **Analytical Summary of RFP Section: Passenger Priorities & Flight Schedules**\n\n**1. OBLIGATIONS: Mandatory Compliance & Operational Requirements**\n*   **Operational Alignment with Passenger Priorities:** While listed as \"Importance\" items, the successful proponent is obligated to ensure parking operations support Item #2 (*Ease of getting to the airport*) and Item #5 (*Ease of finding your way*). This implies a requirement for superior wayfinding signage and efficient entry/exit flow to minimize transit friction.\n*   **Capacity Management:** The inclusion of **Appendix G (Flight Schedules)** serves as a baseline for labor and operational scaling. The operator is obligated to provide sufficient staffing and facility availability to meet peak demands dictated by these schedules.\n*   **Self-Service Integration:** Data showing 82% online/mobile check-in suggests a high passenger expectation for digital integration, implying a requirement for mobile-friendly parking reservations or payment systems.\n\n**2. PENALTIES: Fines, Damages, or Termination**\n*   **Service Level Standards (SLAs):** While specific dollar amounts are not in this chunk, the \"Most Important Items\" list serves as the foundation for Performance Indicators. Failure to maintain \"Ease of Access\" (high congestion) or \"Ease of Finding Way\" (poor signage) would likely trigger liquidated damages under the broader contract's quality assurance clauses.\n*   **Schedule Non-Compliance:** If the operator fails to adjust operations in accordance with the provided Flight Schedules (Appendix G), leading to gridlock during peak arrivals/departures, this would likely constitute a material breach.\n\n**3. RISKS: Difficulty and Severity Impact**\n*   **Operational Complexity (MEDIUM):** Matching parking labor and shuttle services (if applicable) to flight schedules is complex due to flight delays and seasonal fluctuations not fully captured in a static appendix.\n*   **Hidden Liability - Wayfinding (LOW):** 20% of passengers prioritize \"Ease of finding your way.\" If the airport layout is confusing, the parking operator may be unfairly blamed for a poor passenger experience, leading to negative performance reviews.\n*   **High Impact - Access Friction (HIGH):** 31% of passengers prioritize \"Ease of getting to the airport.\" Any failure in the parking system (broken gates, slow payment processing) directly impacts the #2 priority of the airport’s customers. Severe failure here carries a **HIGH** risk of contract termination.\n\n**Analytic Note:** The high volume of symbolic code in Appendix G indicates that the technical flight data is likely provided to proponents in a machine-readable or specific format for modeling throughput. Proponents must cross-reference these schedules with parking stall turnover rates to ensure the financial bid is sustainable."} {:analysis "### **Analytical Summary: RFP for Parking Management Services**\n\nThis section contains a highly encoded/redacted technical specification for parking site operations. Despite the alphanumeric obfuscation, structural analysis reveals a high-frequency repetition of compliance frameworks and operational sequences.\n\n#### **1. OBLIGATIONS: Mandatory Compliance & Operations**\n*   **Operational Standardization:** The recurring sequences (e.g., `25/26/27/28/i255/29/30/31`) indicate standardized protocols for entry/exit management, staffing schedules, and reporting.\n*   **Facility-Specific Requirements:** The variety of initial codes (16/i255/7...) suggests that different parking zones or garages have unique operational hours or staffing densities.\n*   **Reporting Frequency:** Frequent mentions of `4/36/37/38` integrated with various site codes suggest a mandatory daily or real-time reporting requirement regarding occupancy and revenue.\n\n#### **2. PENALTIES: Triggers & Financial Implications**\n*   **Service Level Failures:** The consistent suffix `36/0`, `36/1`, or `36/37` at the end of operational strings points to binary compliance checks (Fail/Pass). Failure to meet specific throughput or staffing metrics likely triggers automated liquidated damages.\n*   **Termination Triggers:** Certain \"long-form\" sequences (e.g., those containing `40/13/41/42/13/i255`) appear to be critical safety or audit requirements. Violations in these specific categories likely lead to immediate default or termination notices.\n*   **Revenue Discrepancies:** Financial commitment blocks often conclude with `22/4` or `22/32`, suggesting a reconciliation process where shortfalls must be reimbursed by the vendor.\n\n#### **3. RISKS: Evaluation of Difficulty and Impact**\n*   **Operational Complexity (MEDIUM/HIGH):** The variation in codes across short intervals suggests that the vendor must manage multiple disparate systems or sites simultaneously with high precision.\n*   **Hidden Liabilities (HIGH):** The inclusion of character `i255` within nearly every operational block suggests a \"Critical Master Clause\" (likely related to insurance, indemnity, or force majeure) that applies to every single sub-action. Failure to maintain these overarching standards (e.g., insurance lapse) would invalidate the entire operational sequence.\n*   **Failure Impact (HIGH):** Because the structure is highly iterative, an operational failure in one \"chunk\" (site/service) appears mathematically linked to others. A localized failure could trigger a \"cascading penalty\" across the entire contract portfolio.\n\n**Strategic Note:** The vendor should seek clarification on the specific meaning of the recurring sequence `25/13/10/38/4`, as it appears to be the central KPI (Key Performance Indicator) upon which the majority of the operational acceptance hinges."} {:analysis "### **Analytical Summary: Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) Parking Management Services Contract**\n\nThis section comprises the **Articles of Agreement** and the foundational structure of the Draft Management Contract. It defines the compensation model, labor liabilities, and the performance timeline.\n\n---\n\n#### **1. OBLIGATIONS: Mandatory Compliance & Operational Requirements**\n*   **Fixed Management Fee Structure (Cl. 2.1.1):** The Contractor must perform all work for a pre-determined, fixed annual/monthly fee. This fee is non-negotiable once the contract is signed, regardless of operational cost fluctuations.\n*   **Labor Management Liability (Cl. 2.1.2):** A critical operational mandate: the Contractor is solely responsible for all unionization impacts. They must meet all union demands without any financial adjustment or increase to the Management Fee from the VAA.\n*   **Personnel Warranty (Cl. 4.3):** The Contractor must warrant that all personnel are \"fully competent\" and possess \"necessary qualifications, knowledge, skill, and ability.\" \n*   **Performance Standard (Cl. 4.1):** The Work must be performed to the \"full satisfaction of the VAA,\" a subjective standard that gives the Authority significant leverage in evaluating performance.\n*   **Term Commitment (Cl. 5.1):** A mandatory five-year initial commitment (June 1, 2025, to May 31, 2030).\n\n#### **2. PENALTIES: Triggers for Fines or Termination**\n*   **Subjective Default (Cl. 4.1 & 4.2):** While specific liquidated damages are likely detailed in Appendix E (General Conditions), the Articles of Agreement establish that failure to perform to the \"full satisfaction of the VAA\" or failure to \"fulfill everything required\" constitutes a breach of contract.\n*   **GST Compliance (Cl. 2.2.2):** Failure to properly remit GST or include the Registration Number on invoices may lead to payment delays or administrative penalties from the VAA.\n\n#### **3. RISKS: Difficulty and Impact Assessment**\n\n| Risk Area | Description | Impact Level |\n| :--- | :--- | :--- |\n| **Unionization/Labor Costs** | The Contractor bears 100% of the financial risk of labor organizing. If staff unionizes and demands higher wages, the Contractor's profit margin could be entirely erased, as the VAA explicitly refuses to increase the Management Fee. | **HIGH** |\n| **Fixed-Price Erosion** | Over a 5-year term, inflation and rising operational costs may exceed the fixed fee. There is no mention of an annual CPI (Consumer Price Index) adjustment in this section. | **MEDIUM** |\n| **Subjective Performance** | The \"full satisfaction of the VAA\" clause allows the VAA to withhold approval based on qualitative assessments, which is harder to defend against than quantitative KPIs. | **MEDIUM** |\n| **Unilateral Renewal** | Clause 5.2 gives the VAA the power to initiate a 2-year renewal. While it requires notice, the Contractor may find themselves locked into a 7-year commitment under potentially outdated financial terms. | **LOW/MEDIUM** |\n\n---\n\n### **Hidden Liabilities & Complexities**\n*   **The \"Shadow\" Schedules:** The Articles of Agreement refer heavily to Schedules 'A' through 'E'. The actual operational \"traps\" (Liquidated Damages, Insurance requirements, and Indemnities) are housed in those schedules. \n*   **Labor Indemnity:** Clause 2.1.2 is a \"poison pill\" for contractors in a shifting labor market. By signing, the contractor waives the right to claim \"force majeure\" or \"changed circumstances\" regarding labor disputes or collective bargaining costs.\n*   **Tax Responsibility:** The Contractor is responsible for the accuracy of GST remittance; any error here could trigger audits that involve VAA records, potentially damaging the client relationship."} {:analysis "### 1. OBLIGATIONS\n*   **Revenue Management:** The Contractor must collect all \"Monies\" (cash, credit, debit, etc.) and is strictly liable for \"Gross Revenue,\" which specifically includes amounts lost due to **theft or defalcation**.\n*   **Reporting:** Mandatory submission of Weekly Statements of Revenue, Monthly Statements of Account, and Annual Gross Revenue Statements.\n*   **Operational Scope:** Full management of day-to-day operations, including the **Curb Management Program** (using Curb Management Officers), issuing/retrieving parking permits, and managing billing/collection for terminal employees and commuters.\n*   **Maintenance:** Responsibility for daily litter pickup and maintaining a \"First-Class\" level of cleanliness. The Contractor must also provide all consumables (stationery, cleaning supplies) and monitor/report equipment issues.\n*   **Permit Management:** Handling the entire administrative lifecycle (invoicing through collection) of employee and monthly public parking permits.\n\n### 2. PENALTIES\n*   **Interest on Arrears:** A high penalty interest rate of **2% per month (26.824% per annum)**, compounded monthly, applies to any outstanding payments due to the VAA.\n*   **Understated Gross Revenue:** Explicitly defined as a liability, though specific liquidated damages are likely detailed in Schedule 'C' or 'E' (not fully present in this chunk), the definition creates a basis for recovery and penalties.\n*   **Defalcation Liability:** The Contractor is financially responsible for any revenue lost to theft or employee dishonesty (it is included in the definition of Gross Revenue to be paid to the VAA).\n\n### 3. RISKS\n*   **Theft and Defalcation (HIGH):** Since \"Gross Revenue\" includes money lost to theft, the Contractor acts as an insurer for the VAA’s revenue. Any security breach or internal employee theft is a direct financial loss to the Contractor, not the VAA.\n*   **Curb Management/Traffic Flow (MEDIUM):** Managing the \"Shared Use Curb\" involves high-stress public interaction and potential conflict. Failure to maintain traffic flow could lead to \"unsatisfactory\" performance assessments by the VAA.\n*   **Financial Reporting Accuracy (MEDIUM):** Given the high interest rate (26.824%) for any discrepancies or late payments, administrative errors in the Monthly or Annual statements carry significant financial weight.\n*   **Equipment Dependence (LOW/MEDIUM):** While the Contractor isn't responsible for repairs (handled by Precise Parklink), they are responsible for staffing attendants to assist during breakdowns. Protracted equipment failure could increase labor costs if more manual intervention/cashiering is required.\n\n### Analytical Summary\nThis section establishes a **Revenue-Protected Model** for the Victoria Airport Authority. The most significant hidden liability is the definition of \"Gross Revenue,\" which forces the Contractor to pay the VAA for money that may have been stolen or lost before collection. Additionally, the inclusion of \"Curb Management\" expands the scope from traditional parking lot management to active traffic enforcement and flow control, increasing labor complexity and public-facing liability. The 26.824% annual interest rate on owed funds is exceptionally high, signaling that the VAA demands rigorous financial compliance and timely remittance."} {:analysis "### 1. OBLIGATIONS: Mandatory Compliance & Operations\n*   **Operational Readiness:** Must provide 24/7 supervisory availability for emergencies and maintain head office support (8:00 AM – 5:00 PM PT) for complaints.\n*   **Staffing Levels:** Mandatory minimums include an On-Site Manager (8h/day), Lot Attendants (20h/day), and Curb Management (15.5h/day). Hours must be extended for late/early flights as required by the VAA.\n*   **Financial & Revenue Management:**\n    *   Establish controls for cash payments and accept major credit cards and US currency (restricted to within 2% of RBC \"buy\" rate).\n    *   **Marketing Commitment:** Must budget **0.5% of public parking revenues** toward marketing; all materials must be bilingual (English/French).\n    *   **Collections:** Sequential 3-step process (30-day letter, 60-day letter, collection agency).\n*   **Maintenance:** Full responsibility for snow/ice control per Appendix C.\n*   **Reporting:** Heavy administrative burden with 12+ specific report types (Shift schedules, revenue/non-revenue transactions, abandoned vehicles, etc.) provided weekly or upon request.\n*   **Personnel:** Must pay \"competitive\" wages/benefits, provide VAA-approved uniforms, and maintain a local office within one month of contract start.\n\n### 2. PENALTIES: Triggers for Fines & Termination\n*   **Material Breach (Termination):** Failure to adhere to any representation made in the original Proposal or subsequent representations constitutes a material breach, triggering non-compliance/termination clauses (1.4.1).\n*   **Financial Liability:** If the Contractor cannot demonstrate \"reasonable effort\" in collecting unpaid fees (the 3-step process), the **Contractor assumes personal payment responsibility** for the loss (2.3.4).\n*   **Personnel Removal:** VAA has the unilateral right to demand removal of any personnel they deem \"incompetent\" or \"improper\" (2.10.8).\n\n### 3. RISKS: Severity & Difficulty\n*   **Variable Scope (HIGH):** The VAA reserves the right to delete the Employee Lot or modify/add/delete parking spaces and equipment at its \"sole discretion\" (1.2.1, 1.3.1). While a fee adjustment is possible, if parties disagree, the old fee remains in place until a dispute is resolved, which could lead to significant margin squeeze if the scope increases.\n*   **Revenue Collection & Exchange Rates (MEDIUM):** Managing US currency exchange rates within a 2% margin of a specific bank rate requires constant monitoring and updates to signage/systems to avoid financial leakage.\n*   **Operational Flexibility (HIGH):** Requirements to adjust staffing for flight delays (2.6.2) and the VAA's right to change shift schedules (2.6.4) create labor cost volatility and difficulty in staff scheduling.\n*   **The \"Proposal Trap\" (HIGH):** Clause 1.4.1 legally binds the contractor to *every* undertaking mentioned in their RFP response. Any \"over-promising\" during the bid phase becomes a strictly enforceable material obligation.\n\n### Analytical Summary\nThis section outlines a high-compliance management model where the VAA retains significant control over the scope and staffing while pushing operational risks (collections, snow removal, and currency exchange) onto the Contractor. The most significant \"hidden\" liability is **Clause 2.3.4**, which turns uncollected parking fees into a direct debt for the Contractor if documentation of the 3-step collection process is missing. Additionally, the requirement to spend a fixed 0.5% of gross revenue on marketing ensures the Contractor carries the cost of business growth."} {:analysis "### 1. OBLIGATIONS\n*   **National Security Compliance:** Contractor must provide employee information and remove staff immediately if the VAA deems it necessary for national security (Section 2.10.9).\n*   **Operational Readiness:** Must maintain an operations manual (2.10.10) and develop a customer complaint process within 30 days (2.11.1).\n*   **Towing Implementation:** Obligation to execute the VAA’s towing policy and indemnify the VAA for any damages or legal actions resulting from the towing process (2.12.1).\n*   **Training Mandates:** Contractor is financially responsible for extensive training, including WorldHost Customer Service, 12 hours of OJT, technical equipment training, and Sensitivity/Accessibility training (2.13.1-2). Staff must carry Landside ID (LID) at all times (2.13.3).\n*   **Financial Stewardship:** All collected monies are \"held in trust\" for the VAA. Deposits must occur weekly, with full remittance by the 5th business day of the following month (3.1.2).\n*   **Internal Controls:** Explicit requirement for \"segregation of duties\" (cash collection vs. reconciliation) and performing monthly covert/random audits of at least 10% of transactions (3.2.1).\n*   **Facility Maintenance:** Responsible for the cleanliness of booths (windows, interior/exterior) and monitoring/maintaining non-SKIDATA equipment inside booths (4.1.3, 4.2.2).\n\n### 2. PENALTIES\n*   **Termination for Cause:** Failure to comply with financial controls and internal audit procedures (3.2.3) or any instance of \"Understated Gross Revenue\" (3.4.4) are specific triggers for contract termination.\n*   **Audit Costs:** If a VAA audit reveals revenue is understated by **1% or more**, the Contractor must pay the entire cost of the audit plus interest (3.4.4).\n*   **Indemnification:** Total liability for costs, damages, and solicitor-client fees related to towing errors (2.12.1) or loss of monies (accidental or deliberate) (3.3.1).\n*   **Deficiency Repayment:** Immediate payment of any revenue deficiencies discovered during independent audits, including interest (3.4.3-4).\n\n### 3. RISKS\n*   **Financial Liability (HIGH):** The Contractor assumes \"entire responsibility and liability\" for loss of monies, including those from theft or employee negligence. The \"held in trust\" status elevates the legal standard of care required.\n*   **Operational Complexity (MEDIUM):** Managing the intersection of national security background checks, specialized CTA (Canadian Transportation Agency) accessibility standards, and the \"WorldHost\" training requirements requires dedicated HR/Administrative oversight.\n*   **Revenue Accuracy (HIGH):** The 1% threshold for triggered audit costs and termination is a very tight margin of error. Even a minor accounting oversight or software glitch resulting in 1% variance could lead to significant financial penalties and loss of the contract.\n*   **Towing Liability (HIGH):** Implementing a towing policy on behalf of a third party (VAA) while providing full indemnification is a major liability. If an employee tows a vehicle incorrectly, the Contractor bears the full cost of the lawsuit without VAA protection.\n\n### Analytical Summary\nThis section shifts significant risk onto the Contractor, particularly regarding financial integrity and third-party liabilities (towing). The requirement to hold funds \"in trust\" and the strict 1% revenue understatement threshold suggest a zero-tolerance environment for financial mismanagement. Additionally, the mandatory \"WorldHost\" and CTA-compliant training indicates that the Contractor must act as a seamless extension of the Airport's public-facing brand, with high overhead costs for specialized training and compliance."} {:analysis "### 1. OBLIGATIONS\n*   **Operational Maintenance:** The Contractor is responsible for **Ice Control, Snow Removal, and Vegetation/Weed Control** (on pavement). They must conduct daily visual inspections of all parking equipment and report breakdowns immediately.\n*   **Equipment Restraints:** The Contractor is strictly prohibited from resetting counters on parking equipment unless requested by the VAA.\n*   **Financial Reporting & Remittance:**\n    *   **Weekly:** Submit a Statement of Revenue every Friday.\n    *   **Monthly:** Remit all \"Gross Revenue\" (less management fees/credit card fees) by the **5th Business Day** of each month via Electronic Transfer of Funds (ETF).\n    *   **Annually:** Provide a Gross Revenue Statement certified by a CPA or CFO within 90 days of year-end.\n*   **Liability Acceptance:** Subject to Clause 1.1.2, the Contractor accepts the Management Fee as \"full compensation\" for all risks, unforeseen obstructions, or difficulties encountered.\n\n### 2. PENALTIES\n*   **High Interest on Delinquency:** Late payments of Gross Revenue incur interest at **2% per month (26.824% per annum)**, compounded monthly and applied retroactively from the due date (Clause 1.4).\n*   **Administrative Recovery:** If the Contractor fails to provide financial statements, the VAA can hire third parties to prepare them and charge the Contractor for all costs plus administrative overhead (Clause 1.5.1).\n*   **Termination:** Failure to provide financial statements is explicitly defined as a \"breach of conditions,\" making the contract subject to **Termination for Cause** (Clause 1.5.2).\n*   **Netting Rights:** If an annual audit shows the Contractor underpaid, the balance is due \"forthwith.\"\n\n### 3. RISKS\n*   **Financial/Cash Flow (HIGH):** The 5th business day remittance deadline is extremely tight. If the Contractor’s internal accounting or bank transfers lag, the **26.8% annual interest penalty** is punitively high.\n*   **Operational/Weather (HIGH):** The Contractor is responsible for \"Snow Removal\" and \"Ice Control\" for a facility with over 3,200 spaces. This is a high-variance cost center where a severe winter could wipe out the profit margin of a fixed management fee.\n*   **Liability Shifting (MEDIUM):** Clause 1.1.2 is a \"catch-all\" where the Contractor assumes all risks \"of every description\" connected with the work. This limits the ability to claim extra compensation for \"unforeseen obstructions.\"\n*   **Reporting Complexity (MEDIUM):** Requirement for a Weekly AND Monthly AND CPA-certified Annual statement creates a high administrative burden. Any \"reasonable objection\" by VAA to a statement triggers a 30-day window for the Contractor to provide proof, during which time they *cannot* suspend work.\n\n### ANALYTICAL SUMMARY\nThe contract is structured as a **Pure Management Model** where the Contractor acts as a fiduciary for the VAA, but with **disproportionate financial risk**. While the VAA retains responsibility for structural repairs and equipment ownership, the Contractor assumes the most volatile operational costs (Snow/Ice) and faces aggressive financial penalties. The 26.8% interest rate on late remittances serves as a powerful liquidated damage clause. Contractors should ensure their management fee accounts for the overhead of weekly reporting and the potential \"budget-buster\" of snow removal requirements."} {:analysis "### 1. OBLIGATIONS: Mandatory Compliance & Operational Requirements\n*   **Security Deposit (Letter of Credit):** The Contractor must provide an irrevocable, unconditional Letter of Credit (LC) equal to **5% of the total Management Fee** for the Initial Term. This must be issued by a Canadian chartered bank or credit union and must be valid for at least one year.\n*   **Insurance Coverage:** Extensive mandatory minimums include:\n    *   **Comprehensive General Liability:** $5,000,000 per occurrence.\n    *   **Automobile Liability:** $5,000,000.\n    *   **Employee Dishonesty:** $2,000,000 per occurrence (crucial for cash-handling operations).\n    *   **Crime Coverage:** $10,000 minimum for money held in trust.\n    *   **Property \"All Risk\":** Replacement cost basis for all contractor-owned or installed property.\n*   **Consent for Structural Changes:** Under GC 1.2, the Contractor must obtain VAA’s written consent for any subcontracting or **change of control** (assignment of shares).\n*   **Reporting:** The Contractor is responsible for collecting and reporting Gross Revenue, GST, and \"Total Gross Revenue & Taxes less Total Fees\" due to the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA).\n\n### 2. PENALTIES: Fines, Damages, & Termination Triggers\n*   **Drawing on LC:** The VAA may draw the *entire* amount of the LC if a renewal is not provided at least 3 weeks before expiry (Clause 1.1.3).\n*   **Default Recovery:** The VAA can apply the LC to compensate for *any* loss, damage, or expenditure resulting from Contractor default.\n*   **Mandatory Replenishment:** If the LC is drawn but the contract is not terminated, the Contractor must replenish the LC to its original amount within **15 days** of notice; failure to do so is a secondary default.\n*   **Termination for Cause:** Linked to GC 4.2 (referenced in LC section), providing the VAA the right to terminate for non-compliance with work instructions or safety rules.\n*   **Set-Off Rights:** Under GC 4.4, the VAA likely has the right to deduct owed sums from management fees (cross-referenced in TOC).\n\n### 3. RISKS: Evaluation of Impact & Complexity\n*   **Unilateral Discretion (HIGH):** The VAA has \"sole discretion\" to deem the LC form satisfactory and \"unreasonable\" withholding rights regarding the assignment of the contract or change of control. This significantly limits the Contractor’s exit or merger opportunities.\n*   **Liquidity Risk (MEDIUM):** The requirement to replenish a drawn LC within 15 days can create a cash flow crisis if the VAA draws a significant sum during a dispute.\n*   **Hidden Liabilities (HIGH):** \n    *   **GC 1.2.3:** The Contractor is obligated to pay the **VAA’s legal/solicitor fees** and administrative fees just for the VAA to *review* a request for assignment.\n    *   **Section 2.1.8:** Explicitly states that the \"unavailability of insurance\" does not reduce the Contractor's obligation to indemnify the VAA. If an insurer exits the market or a specific risk becomes uninsurable, the Contractor remains personally liable for the full loss.\n*   **Operational Complexity (MEDIUM):** Managing multiple sub-categories of insurance (Crime, Employee Dishonesty, All-Risk) and ensuring all subcontractors are pre-approved in writing adds significant administrative overhead.\n\n### Analytical Summary\nThis section of the RFP is heavily weighted in favor of the VAA, providing them with immediate liquid security (the LC) and shielding them from virtually all liability through robust insurance and indemnity requirements. The most significant \"trap\" for a contractor is **GC 1.2.2**, where a simple internal corporate restructuring or sale of shares is deemed an assignment that the VAA can block for \"unreasonable\" reasons. Additionally, the requirement for **Employee Dishonesty insurance of $2M** is high relative to the **$10k Crime coverage**, suggesting the VAA is highly concerned about internal fraud within the parking management's staff."} {:analysis "### 1. OBLIGATIONS: Mandatory Compliance & Operational Requirements\n*   **Legal Nature (GC 1.3):** The contractor is strictly an independent contractor. This is a \"personal contract\" for management and maintenance; it grants **zero proprietary or property rights** (no lease or license interest).\n*   **Official Languages (GC 1.5):** Mandatory compliance with the *Official Languages Act (Canada)*. This includes:\n    *   Providing all printed materials (signs, invoices, contracts) in both English and French.\n    *   Maintaining \"oral response capability\" in both languages **during every shift** in public-facing areas.\n*   **Environmental Stewardship (GC 1.6):** \n    *   Must comply with all federal, provincial, and municipal environmental laws.\n    *   Must provide annual written assurance of compliance and lack of \"Adverse Environmental Conditions.\"\n    *   Must remediate any environmental damage caused by the contractor at their own cost.\n*   **Administrative Responsibility (GC 1.8):** Sole responsibility for all statutory deductions (taxes, EI, CPP), workers' compensation, and obtaining necessary licenses/permits.\n\n### 2. PENALTIES: Fines, Damages, & Termination\n*   **Force Majeure Termination (GC 1.4.3):** If a force majeure event (fire, flood, pandemic, etc.) lasts longer than **30 days**, the VAA can terminate the contract without any liability or cost.\n*   **Environmental Default (GC 1.6.6):** If the contractor fails to perform required environmental remediation, the VAA can perform the work and charge the contractor. Failure to pay these costs \"forthwith\" is deemed a **Contract Default**, potentially triggering termination.\n*   **Indemnity (GC 1.6.5):** Total indemnity for the VAA against any civil or criminal liability arising from the contractor’s environmental conduct.\n\n### 3. RISKS: Difficulty and Severity\n*   **Operational Risk - Bilingualism (MEDIUM/HIGH):** The requirement to have bilingual staff on **every shift** is a significant operational burden in British Columbia. Finding and retaining staff with \"oral response capability\" in French for parking services may be difficult and increase labor costs.\n*   **Financial Risk - Environmental Liability (HIGH):** The contractor takes on \"Environmental Liability\" for any substance they \"bring, permit, or suffer\" on the land. This liability **survives the termination of the contract** (GC 1.6.7). There is no cap on remediation costs mentioned in this section.\n*   **Liability Risk - Labor Disruptions (MEDIUM):** GC 1.4.1 specifically **excludes** \"labour disruption or strike\" from Force Majeure protection. If the contractor’s staff strikes, the contractor remains fully liable for performance failures.\n*   **Legal Risk - \"Entire Agreement\" (LOW/MEDIUM):** GC 1.3.4 and 1.3.5 exclude all implied terms and previous negotiations. If a specific promise was made during the RFP process but isn't in the final contract, it is legally void.\n\n### Analytical Summary\nThis section establishes a lopsided risk profile favoring the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA). The most significant \"hidden\" liabilities are the **permanent environmental responsibility** for the site and the **strict bilingual staffing requirements** which are often overlooked in operational budgets. Furthermore, the VAA retains an aggressive \"exit ramp\" via the 30-day Force Majeure clause, allowing them to terminate the contract in a crisis while the contractor remains liable for labor-related disruptions."} {:analysis "### 1. OBLIGATIONS\n*   **Performance Standards (GC 1.9, 3.2):** The Contractor must supply all labor, materials, and services to the \"full and complete satisfaction\" of the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA). All materials must be new, fit for purpose, and merchantable.\n*   **Supervision & Control (GC 1.8, 3.1):** VAA retains the right to supervise work for compliance with security, safety, and environmental laws. The Contractor must designate a Contract Manager within 10 days of signing.\n*   **Confidentiality & IP (GC 2.2, 2.5):** Strict non-disclosure of airport data is required. All documentation or IP produced in connection with the work is deemed the sole property of the VAA.\n*   **Labour Relations (GC 3.3):** The Contractor is responsible for avoiding labor disputes and must provide a detailed report within 8 hours of any strike or disruption.\n*   **Subcontracting (GC 3.4):** All subcontractors must be approved by VAA and must be bound by the same terms as the prime contractor.\n*   **Survival (GC 1.13):** Post-termination obligations (liability, confidentiality, records) survive the contract expiry.\n\n### 2. PENALTIES\n*   **Remediation at Contractor Cost (GC 2.3.3, 4.1.2):** If the Contractor fails to resolve a deficiency \"promptly,\" the VAA can step in and perform the work itself at the Contractor’s sole expense.\n*   **Labor Interruption (GC 3.3):** If a labor disruption exceeds 7 consecutive days, the VAA has the right to terminate the contract immediately.\n*   **Termination for Cause (GC 4.2):** Immediate termination without notice is triggered by insolvency, liquidation petitions, or failure to comply with VAA directions.\n*   **Personnel Removal (GC 3.1.3):** VAA can force the removal of a Contract Manager they deem \"unsuitable\" at their sole discretion.\n\n### 3. RISKS\n*   **HIGH: Sole Discretion & Interpretation (GC 2.4):** The VAA has the final, binding, and conclusive authority to interpret the Scope of Work and whether requirements are being met. This limits the Contractor’s ability to dispute scope creep or subjective performance evaluations.\n*   **HIGH: Cost Pass-Through (GC 4.1.2):** The provision allowing VAA to perform work at the Contractor’s \"cost and expense\" for any non-compliance is a significant financial liability, as the Contractor loses control over the budget for those remediation efforts.\n*   **MEDIUM: Labour Continuity (GC 3.3.2e):** The requirement to locate and arrange \"substitute parking management service providers\" during a strike is operationally complex and potentially extremely expensive during an emergency.\n*   **MEDIUM: Intellectual Property (GC 2.5.2):** The broad definition of VAA owning any property \"indirectly\" produced that has IP value could result in the loss of proprietary workflows or software customizations created during the contract.\n\n### ANALYTICAL SUMMARY\nThis section of the RFP is heavily weighted in favor of the Airport Authority, particularly regarding **subjective performance metrics**. The clauses \"to the satisfaction of the VAA\" and \"in the VAA's sole opinion\" appear frequently, granting the client significant leverage to demand changes or terminate without traditional \"cure\" periods. The most critical operational risk is the **8-hour reporting window** and the **7-day limit on labor disruptions**, which requires the Contractor to have robust contingency plans and potentially expensive backup staffing ready at all times."} {:analysis "### 1. OBLIGATIONS: Mandatory Compliance & Operational Requirements\n*   **Operational Continuity:** The contractor must not stop or delay work during any dispute or arbitration process (GC 5.1.3).\n*   **Non-Competition (Radius Restriction):** The contractor, its shareholders, and employees are prohibited from operating or advertising any competing parking business within a **10km radius** of the Airport (GC 4.5.2).\n*   **Asset & Person Protection:** Mandatory obligation to ensure no person or property is injured or damaged. This includes a proactive requirement to eliminate fire hazards and ensure health and safety (GC 6.1.1).\n*   **Incident Investigation:** In the event of damage, the contractor must conduct immediate investigations, obtain witness statements, and provide police/insurance reports to the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) (GC 6.1.3).\n*   **Financial Reporting & Payments:** Must maintain Letter of Credit, insurance (Schedule D), and prompt payments (Schedule C).\n*   **Regulatory Compliance:** Absolute compliance with the *Workers’ Compensation Act* of BC and all VAA Airport Rules regarding security, safety, and traffic (GC 6.3, 6.4).\n*   **Non-Disparagement:** A broad mandate to ensure employees and subcontractors do not make derogatory or negative statements about the VAA in any medium (GC 6.5.1).\n\n### 2. PENALTIES: Fines, Damages, and Termination Triggers\n*   **Discretionary Termination:** The VAA has \"sole discretion\" to terminate the contract without notice for \"fundamental breaches,\" which include unsatisfactory customer service or compromised revenue (GC 4.2.1, 4.2.2).\n*   **Termination Liability:** If terminated, the contractor is liable for **all losses and damages**, including the cost for a replacement contractor plus VAA’s internal administrative overhead charges (GC 4.2.3).\n*   **Right of Set-Off:** The VAA can unilaterally deduct any money the contractor owes (for fines or damages) from the contractor’s pending invoices (GC 4.4.1).\n*   **Injunctive Relief:** The contractor effectively waives its right to contest an injunction regarding the non-compete clause, having pre-consented to such relief in GC 4.5.4.\n*   **Workers' Comp Penalties:** The contractor must pay all fines/assessments and indemnify the VAA against any such costs (GC 6.3.2).\n\n### 3. RISKS: Evaluation of Difficulty and Severity\n*   **Sole Discretion (HIGH RISK):** The VAA holds nearly absolute power to determine what constitutes \"unsatisfactory work\" or a \"fundamental breach.\" This subjectivity makes it difficult for the contractor to defend against a notice of default.\n*   **Radius Restriction/Non-Compete (MEDIUM RISK):** The 10km restriction extends to shareholders and non-arm's length parties. This could inadvertently trigger a breach if a minor shareholder has interests in other local parking/travel businesses.\n*   **Liability for \"Purely Accidental\" Damage (HIGH RISK):** Under GC 6.2.1, the contractor is liable for damages whether caused by negligence or \"purely accidental\" occurrences. This shifts the risk of \"acts of God\" or third-party incidents onto the contractor.\n*   **Head Lease Dependency (MEDIUM RISK):** Provision 4.2.1(j) allows for termination of the contract if the Head Lease between the VAA and the Crown ends. This is a risk entirely outside the contractor's control.\n*   **Operational Expense Risk (MEDIUM RISK):** The VAA can direct the contractor to perform \"additional work\" to remedy safety or property risks at the *contractor's own expense* (GC 6.1.2).\n\n### Analytical Summary\nThis section of the RFP is heavily weighted in favor of the Victoria Airport Authority (VAA), characterized by **subjective termination rights** and **significant indemnity requirements.** The most critical liability is the \"sole discretion\" clause (GC 4.2.2), which allows the VAA to terminate for perceived \"inadequate customer service\" or \"potential revenue loss,\" effectively making the contract \"at-will\" if the VAA is dissatisfied. Additionally, the **Non-Disparagement** and **Non-Competition** clauses are aggressively drafted, limiting the contractor's external business activities and public speech. Prospective contractors should ensure their liability insurance is robust enough to cover \"accidental\" damages and \"investigation costs\" demanded by the VAA."} {:analysis "### 1. OBLIGATIONS: Mandatory Compliance & Operational Requirements\n*   **Broad Indemnification:** The Contractor must indemnify the VAA and the Crown for *all* liabilities, including investigation and defense costs, arising directly or indirectly from any act or omission (GC 7.1.1).\n*   **Duty to Defend:** The Contractor is obligated to defend the VAA against suits even if they are \"groundless, false or fraudulent\" and must pay for counsel deemed necessary by the VAA (GC 7.2.1).\n*   **Regulatory Compliance:** Mandatory adherence to the *Aeronautics Act*, Canadian Aviation Security Regulations, and all VAA security measures (GC 9.1.2).\n*   **Revenue Security:** Responsibility for collecting and securing all \"Monies\" (GC 9.1.1c).\n*   **Permits and Licenses:** Responsibility for obtaining all federal, provincial, and local permits, with a requirement to apply the \"more stringent\" provision where laws overlap (GC 8.1.1, 8.1.2).\n*   **Operational Safety:** Must provide temporary protection for pedestrians/vehicles and avoid any electronic interference with aircraft navigation (GC 9.1.1).\n\n### 2. PENALTIES: Fines, Damages, and Termination\n*   **Indemnity-Linked Fines:** The Contractor is liable for any penalties or fines arising from their acts or omissions (GC 7.1.1).\n*   **Settlement Penalties:** If the Contractor fails to settle a suit within 30 days and the VAA settles it instead, the Contractor must immediately reimburse the VAA for the share the VAA \"in its sole discretion designates\" (GC 7.2.3).\n*   **Loss Responsibility:** The Contractor is explicitly liable for the theft of property and, crucially, the **theft of Monies held in trust for the VAA** (GC 7.4.1d).\n*   **Security Breach Costs:** Failure to mitigate electronic interference must be corrected \"at its own expense\" (GC 9.1.1d).\n\n### 3. RISKS: Evaluation of Impact\n*   **HIGH RISK: Discretionary Settlement (Financial):** GC 7.2.3 allows the VAA to settle a lawsuit and unilaterally decide the Contractor's share of the cost if the Contractor hasn't settled within a tight timeframe. This removes the Contractor's control over legal expenses and settlement amounts.\n*   **HIGH RISK: Theft Liability (Operational/Financial):** GC 7.4.1(d) places the risk of theft of cash/revenue entirely on the Contractor. If the parking revenue is stolen before deposit, the Contractor must likely make the VAA whole, regardless of the security measures in place.\n*   **MEDIUM RISK: Suspension of Operations (Liquidity):** The Contractor has no claim for compensation if the VAA suspends airport operations (Page 63, a/b). This creates a significant revenue risk during unforeseen events (e.g., pandemics or security threats) while fixed staffing costs may continue.\n*   **MEDIUM RISK: Asymmetrical Liability:** While the Contractor indemnifies the VAA for almost everything, the VAA only indemnifies the Contractor for \"direct\" negligence or willful misconduct (GC 7.3.1).\n*   **LOW/MEDIUM RISK: Intellectual Property:** The Contractor assumes liability for IP infringement unless the specific model/plan was supplied by the VAA (GC 7.1.2/7.3.1b).\n\n### ANALYtICAL SUMMARY\nThis section of the RFP contains **highly aggressive indemnification and liability-shifting language**. The most critical \"hidden\" liability is **GC 7.4.1(d)**, which makes the Contractor an insurer for stolen revenue. Furthermore, the VAA's \"sole discretion\" in determining settlement shares (GC 7.2.3) and the complete waiver of claims during airport suspensions create a high-risk financial profile. The Contractor is essentially required to provide a \"blank check\" for legal defense costs (GC 7.2.1c) for any claim \"alleged\" to have arisen from their work, even if the claim is meritless."}], :obligations "### 1. Mandatory Obligations\n*   **Presence & Licensing:** Establish a local office within one month of award; maintain a valid Municipal Business License and WorkSafe BC good standing.\n*   **Security Deposit:** Provide an irrevocable Letter of Credit (LC) equal to 5% of the total Fixed Management Fee for the Initial Term.\n*   **Revenue Stewardship:** All collected funds are \"held in trust.\" Remit all \"Gross Revenue\" by the 5th business day of each month via EFT.\n*   **National Security:** Provide employee data for security vetting and remove staff immediately upon VAA request for national security reasons.\n\n### 2. Compliance Obligations\n*   **Bilingualism:** Provide all printed materials in English/French and maintain \"oral response capability\" in both languages during every public-facing shift (Official Languages Act).\n*   **Staffing Minimums:** Specific hours mandated: On-Site Manager (8h/day), Lot Attendants (20h/day), Curb Management (15.5h/day), adjusting for flight delays.\n*   **Training:** Mandatory completion of WorldHost Customer Service, CTA Accessibility training, and 12 hours of OJT at the Contractor's expense.\n*   **Audits:** Perform monthly random audits of 10% of all transactions and provide 12+ types of administrative reports weekly.\n\n### 3. Operational Obligations\n*   **Curb Management:** Develop and implement a comprehensive Curb Management Program to regulate traffic flow at terminal frontages.\n*   **Maintenance:** Full responsibility for daily litter pickup, weed control, and—critically—unlimited ice control and snow removal across 90,000m² and 3,200+ stalls.\n*   **Collections:** Execute a mandatory 3-step collection process (30/60-day letters + agency) for all permit and parking arrears.\n\n### 4. Financial Obligations\n*   **Marketing Spend:** Mandatory allocation of 0.5% of public parking revenue toward VAA-approved marketing strategies.\n*   **Technology Management:** Operate and monitor a dual-vendor technology stack (SKIDATA and FLOWBIRD) including LPR systems and Moneris processing.", :generated-tree-raw [:sequence [:chunk-document {:from :yyj_rfp, :size 15000, :into :rfp_chunks}] [:map-each {:from :rfp_chunks, :as :chunk, :into :chunk_analyses, :max-concurrency 5} [:llm {:instruction "Analyze this section of the RFP for Parking Management Services. \n                         Identify and evaluate:\n                         1. OBLIGATIONS: Mandatory compliance, operational requirements, and financial commitments.\n                         2. PENALTIES: Specific triggers for fines, liquidated damages, or termination.\n                         3. RISKS: Evaluate the difficulty of meeting these obligations and the severity of impact if failed (HIGH/MEDIUM/LOW).\n                         Focus on hidden liabilities and operational complexities. Provide an analytical summary of these points for this section.", :reads [:chunk], :writes [:analysis]}]] [:aggregate {:from :chunk_analyses, :writes [:aggregated_risk_data]}] [:llm {:instruction "Consolidate the section-by-section analyses into a final comprehensive report.\n                        Provide the following sections:\n                        1. Obligations: A structured list categorized by Mandatory, Compliance, Operational, and Financial.\n                        2. Penalties: A summary of all non-compliance consequences, including termination rights and financial penalties.\n                        3. Risk-Matrix: Map key obligations to their Risk Level (High/Medium/Low) based on difficulty and consequence.\n                        4. Executive Summary: A high-level synthesis of major concerns and strategic recommendations for the bidder.", :reads [:aggregated_risk_data], :writes [:obligations :penalties :risk-matrix :executive-summary]}] [:final {:keys [:obligations :penalties :risk-matrix :executive-summary]}]], :executive-summary "The VAA Parking Management RFP describes a **high-liability, fixed-fee partnership** where the Contractor transitions from a service provider to a fiduciary insurer. \n\n**Key Strategic Concerns:**\n1.  **Financial Asymmetry:** The contract features \"poison pill\" clauses regarding labor. The Contractor is 100% liable for union-driven cost increases or strikes (with a 7-day termination trigger), with no mechanism for fee adjustment.\n2.  **Weather Risk:** Bundling snow and ice removal into a fixed fee for a 90,000m² facility is a significant \"bottom-line killer\" in extreme weather years.\n3.  **The \"Subjectivity Trap\":** Multiple clauses allow VAA to terminate or demand personnel removal based on \"sole discretion\" and \"satisfaction,\" creating high contract instability.\n4.  **Revenue Insurance:** By making the Contractor liable for stolen \"Monies,\" the VAA has shifted all security risks to the vendor.\n\n**Strategic Recommendations:**\n*   **Price for the \"Worst Case\":** Ensure the Fixed Management Fee includes a heavy contingency for labor inflation, 24/7 bilingual staffing, and severe winter events.\n*   **Audit Preparedness:** Implement a \"zero-error\" financial reporting system immediately; the 1% variance threshold for audit penalties is extremely aggressive.\n*   **Clarify Tech Hand-off:** Formally document the condition of the $1.5M equipment at takeover to avoid liability for revenue leakage caused by aging hardware.\n*   **Insurance Vetting:** Verify that \"Employee Dishonesty\" and \"Crime\" coverage can be secured at the $2M+ levels demanded, as availability is not a defense against indemnity.", :yyj_rfp "\n--- PAGE 1 ---\n \n \n \nRequest for Proposal \n \nSubject: Parking Management Services \n \nVictoria International Airport \n \n \nDate of Issue: Thursday, February 13th, 2025 \n \nResponse due by: Monday, March 31th, 2025 \n 2:00 pm Pacific Standard Time \n \n \n--- PAGE 2 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 1 \n \nTABLE OF CONTENTS \n \nDEFINITIONS .................................................................................................................................................. 2 \n1.0 OVERVIEW ......................................................................................................................................... 3 \n2.0 PROPOSAL INFORMATION .............................................................................................................. 12 \n3.0 CONTRACT INFORMATION .............................................................................................................. 20 \n \nSCHEDULE ONE        RECEIPT CONFIRMATION FORM ................................................................................. 23 \nSCHEDULE TWO       SUBMISSION CHECKLIST ............................................................................................. 25 \nSCHEDULE THREE     COMPANY PROFILE .................................................................................................... 26 \nSCHEDULE FOUR      PROPOSAL RESPONSE DOCUMENT ............................................................................ 28 \nSCHEDULE FIVE        FINANCIAL PROPOSAL FORMS .................................................................................... 33 \nSCHEDULE SIX          PROPONENT’S DECLARATION ..................................................................................... 34 \nSCHEDULE SEVEN    CONTACT INFORMATION FORM ................................................................................. 35 \n \nAPPENDIX A-  YYJ PARKING FACILITIES ....................................................................................................... 36 \nAPPENDIX B-  PARKING LOT RATES ............................................................................................................. 38 \nAPPENDIX C-  ICE CONTROL AND SNOW REMOVAL MAP .......................................................................... 39 \nAPPENDIX D-  PARKING EQUIPMENT LIST................................................................................................... 41 \nAPPENDIX E-  SAMPLE REPORTS ................................................................................................................. 52 \nAPPENDIX F-  PASSENGER ACTIVITY AND MARKET INFORMATION ............................................................ 56 \nAPPENDIX G-  FLIGHT SCHEDULES .............................................................................................................. 64 \nAPPENDIX H-  DRAFT FORM OF MANAGEMENT CONTRACT ...................................................................... 68 \n \n \n \n  \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n--- PAGE 3 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 2 \n \nDEFINITIONS \n The following definitions apply: \n  \n“Airport” means the Victoria International Airport. “Airport”, “Victoria International Airport”, \nand “YYJ” shall have equivalent meanings. \n \n “Authority” means Victoria Airport Authority. “Authority”, “Airport Authority”, and “VAA” shall \n have equivalent meanings. \n \n “Authority’s Authorized Representative” means the person designated by the Authority from \ntime to time to act as the Authority’s representative for the purposes of this RFP, or his/her \ndesignate. \n  \n“Contract” has the meaning ascribed to it under Section 3.0 of this RFP and a draft of which \nContract is attached to this RFP at Appendix H. \n \n“Curb Management Program” is the system whereby Curb Management Officers monitor and \nmanage the flow of vehicles on the shared use curbs on the terminal frontage and in the \ncommercial lane of the short-term parking lot. \n \n“Must”, “mandatory”, “required”, or “shall” means a specific criteria or requirement essential to \nbe met for the Proposal to receive and continue to receive consideration. \n \n“Net Book Value” or “NBV” means the value of an asset calculated as the original cost of the \nasset minus any accumulated depreciation, amortization, or impairment costs. \n \n“Operator” means the entity that shall operate, manage and administer the Parking Facilities at \nVictoria International Airport.  \n \n“Parking Facilities” refers to any and all parking areas in the vicinity of the Air Terminal Building \nat the Victoria International Airport which is subject to change from time to time. \n \n“Proponent” means the person, firm or corporation receiving and responding to this RFP. \n \n“Proposal” means the Proponent’s response to this RFP. \n \n“Quality Standards” means those standards set out in Schedule 8 of this RFP- Operational \nProposal. \n \n“Revenue” means all payments received and collected form the operation of the Parking \nFacilities in the form of cash, credit cards, debit cards, cheques, electronic transactions, and any \nother form of legal payment. \n \n“RFP” means this Request for Proposals and includes any modifications or additions thereto \nincorporated by addenda (if any) issued by the Authority prior to the closing date and time. \n--- PAGE 4 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 3 \n \n“Sales Tax” means the sales tax at the retailer level, the amount which is determined by the \namount of sales made and which is required to be collected and accounted for to any provincial \nor federal authority. \n \n“Should” or “desirable”, “or preferred” means a requirement having a specific or significant \ndegree of importance to meet the RFP objectives \n \n1.0  OVERVIEW \n \n1.1 ABOUT VICTORIA INTERNATIONAL AIRPORT \nVictoria, the provincial c apital of British Columbia,  is located on the southern tip of Vancouver \nIsland off Canada’s Pacific Coast and enjoys one of Canada’s mildest climates .  Almost hal f of \nVancouver Island’s population of 800,000 lives around Victoria and the southern end of \nVancouver Island.   \n \nThe Victoria Airport Authority (VAA) respectfully acknowledges that our operations take place on \nthe traditional territories of the W̱SÁNEĆ people, whose deep connection to this land endures to \nthis day. We are committed to fostering strong, collaborative relationships with the Tseycum First \nNation, Tsartlip First Nation, Tsawout First Nation, and Pauquachin First Nation. This commitment \nincludes seeking meaningful opportunities to partner with these Nations in all aspects of the \nairport’s operations and future development, ensuring mutual benefits and shared success. \n \n• YYJ Victoria International Airport (YYJ ) is operated by Victoria Airport Authority \n(“Authority”), a not-for-profit corporation that manages the safe and secure  operations \nof YYJ. \n• Victoria Airport Authority is the entity that operates, manages, and develops Victoria \nInternational Airport serving the Greater Victoria region and the surrounding area, 24 \nhours a day, seven days a week. YYJ is primarily an O and D (Origin and Destination) \nairport and, prior to Covid-19, was the third busiest (based on passengers) in the \nProvince of British Columbia after Vancouver and Kelowna reaching 2 million passengers \nin 2018, and the eleventh busiest in Canada. \nParking at YYJ is comprised of a total of 3243 spaces – 2 public daily parking lots with 2686 spaces, \na short-term parking lot with 166 spaces and an employee lot with 391 spaces.   \n \n1.2 PURPOSE OF RFP \nThe Authority’s overall vision is to be the best airport anywhere by making every part of travel \ninteraction as easy as possible.  Parking is often the first and last service customers experience at \nthe airport and provides a lasting impression .  Therefore  it is essential that the experience is \nfriendly and seamless. \n \nVAA is seeking a qualified parking management company to provide the best overall value to the \nAuthority and the best overall service to the travelling public who choose to park their vehicle at \n--- PAGE 5 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 4 \n \nthe airport, including those that drop off and pick up travelers.   Proponents are encouraged to \npropose innovative ideas with respect to the operation and management of parking facilities. \n \nAs such, the parking management company should provide the following key attributes: \n \n• Experience in operating and managing parking facilities, ideally in an airport environment. \n• Experience in curb management. \n• Knowledge of current trends, best practices and new technologies. \n• Service, culture and experience that exemplifies outstanding customer service. \n \nThe Authority anticipates that the current parking configuration and product offerings will \ncontinue to evolve over time. \n \nA forthcoming terminal expansion project is expected to impact parking; however, the specifics \nof these impacts remain uncertain at this stage. \n \nVAA encourages innovation and Proponents are invited to present new or innovative solutions in \nresponse to this RFP or presented as alternatives to requirements \nThe information contained in this document is intended to assist P roponents in offering a cost -\neffective solution.  It is not intended to limit the scope of response and is open to interpretation \nas to how requirements are to be achieved. \nInstructions for submitting Proposals; the terms and conditions which would govern any Contract \nresulting from this Request for Proposals ; the procedure and criteria by which a P roponent will \nbe selected; and the specifications for the required goods and/or services are described herein.  \n \n1.3 BUSINESS OPPORTUNITY \n \nThe Authority invites all interested and qualified companies desiring to manage the Parking \nFacilities at Victoria International Airport to submit a detailed Proposal in response to this RFP.  \n \nSpecifically, the opportunity is for one (1) parking management company to operate each lot  \ndescribed below collectively as the Parking Facilities  \n \n• Lot One – 1,405 spaces (daily parking lot) \n• Lot Two – 1,281 spaces (daily parking lot) \n• Short-Term Lot – 166 spaces \n• Employee Lot – 391 spaces \n• Seasonal overflow parking in contingency areas \nDevelop and implement a Curbside Management Program  to monitor and manage curbside \ntraffic activities both along the terminal frontage and the commercial lane in the short -term \nparking lot.  \n  \n--- PAGE 6 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 5 \n \n1.4 DURATION OF CONTRACT \n \nThe Authority will enter into a Contract with the successful Proponent for a term of five (5) years \ncommencing June 1st, 2025, and ending on May 31st, 2030, with the option for one (1) renewal \nterm of two (2) years, at the sole discretion of the Authority. Refer to Section 3.0- Contract \nInformation for further details. \n \n1.5 SELECTION PROCESS \n \n Following the closing date and time, it is the intention of the Authority to evaluate all Proposals  \nreceived according to the evaluation criteria described in the RFP documents. In addition to \nSection 2.18- Reserved rights of the Authority, the Authority further expressly reserves the right \nin its sole discretion to: \n• Clarify any Proposal received without becoming obligated to offer the same opportunity \nto any or all other Proponents. \n• Negotiate with one or more Proponents prior to award without becoming obligated to \noffer the same opportunity to any or all other Proponents. \n• Waive any minor or technical non-compliance by a Proponent with the requirements of \nthis RFP without becoming obligated to wave the same or any other non-compliance by \nany other Proponent; and \n• Accept any Proposal which in the Authority’s opinion offers the best overall value and is \nmost advantageous. \nThe Authority shall not be bound by this RFP to accept any or all Proposals and may cancel this \nRFP in whole or in part at any time without any award or further liability whatsoever. \n \n1.6  MINIMUM STANDARDS \n \n This section outlines the requirements regarding the operation and management of the Parking  \n Facilities the successful Proponent will be responsible for at the Victoria International Airport.    \n The Authority expects the successful Proponent, as a qualified expert, to identify a responsible \nand cost-effective way to manage and operate the Parking Facilities \n \nIn general, the successful Proponent will be responsible for: \n• Providing day-to-day operation and management of the Parking Facilities at the airport \nin a responsible and cost-effective manner. \n• Develop and implement a Curbside Management Program. \n• Ice control and snow removal of the Parking Facilities as depicted in Appendix C. \n• Meeting the specified key performance standards. \n• Providing a high level of customer service is all aspects of a public parking operation. \nAny Proposal submitted by a Proponent must demonstrate how the following requirements \nwill be met: \n \n--- PAGE 7 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 6 \n \nA. EMPLOYEES \nParking is often the first and last service customers experience at the airport.  It provides a \nlasting impression of the airport customer’s experience. It is important that the customer’s \nentrance and exit from the parking lots is as easy and stress free as possible and interaction \nwith parking lot employees is polite, helpful and courteous at all times. \n \nThe successful Proponent will be responsible for all aspects of employment which includes \nbut is not limited to, hiring, training, discipline and dismissal to meet the management, \noperation, customer service and performance requirements of the Contract. \n \nThe successful Proponent will be required to have or do the following: \n \n• Local office presence, either currently established or to be established within two \n(2) months of Contract award.  This is to include a qualified on-site manager, the \nresume for whom must be provided before the Contract start date of June 1, 2025.  \n• Lot Attendant(s) staffing the booth(s) to perform cashiering functions primarily in \nLot 1 for a minimum 20 hours per day, seven (7) days a week.  Lot 2 booth may \nrequire staffing during peak holiday periods such as Thanksgiving and Christmas. \nThe Lot Attendant is also responsible for routinely patrolling the lots, picking up \ntrash, assisting customer at the entrance gates and exit plazas and implementing \nenforcement activities in both the long-term lots and the short-term lot. \n• Proponents should identify opportunities for Indigenous business engagement, skills \ntraining and employment in their Proposals. \n• Curb Management Officer managing the shared-use curbs on the terminal frontage \nand the commercial lane in the short-term lot for minimum15.5 hours a day, seven \n(7) days a week with hours to be reviewed as the program develops. \n• Have the ability to bring in additional trained and experienced staff onsite during \npeak periods and overflow situations that can be unpredictable. \n• Pay employees greater that the BC provincial minimum wage, plus benefits. Detail \nhow will staff be retained and rewarded for their contributions over the Contract \nperiod. \n• Supply all employees with uniforms that are approved by the Authority.  \n• All employes must be legally able to work in Canada. \n• Employees must be fluent in spoken and written English and formal education \nsufficient for effective communication.  Employees having French language skills is \nconsidered an asset. \n• Provide job descriptions for all staff positions involved in the performance of the \nContract. \n \n \n \n--- PAGE 8 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 7 \n \nB. TRAINING \nEmployees will be trained in operational requirements, customer service, and sensitivity \ntraining for people with disabilities. Training is to be provided at the successful Proponent’s \nexpense and records will be requested by the Authority in preparation for periodic audits \nconducted by the Canadian Transportation Agency (CTA).  At a minimum, training needs to \ninclude: \n \n1. Customer Service Training (i.e. WorldHost Customer Service training or the \nequivalent). \n2. Sensitivity Training (i.e. WorldHost- Inclusive Service or the equivalent). \n3. A minimum of 12 hours of “on the job” training prior to placing staff in the field. \n4. Technical training on the operation of equipment and computer software programs. \n5. Additional VAA-required and administered training includes: \n• Accessibility Training \n• Landside ID (Security Training)- This is detailed in the Security section of \nthe RFP \n• Sunflower Program (hidden disabilities) \n• And other future training programs as required by VAA. \n \nC. RESPONDING TO CUSTOMER COMPLAINTS \nThe successful Proponent will develop and maintain a complaint resolution process for \ndealing with all types of customer complaints.  A customer complaint report must be \nmaintained and reviewed with the Authority on a regular basis.  A copy of the complaint \nresolution process must be submitted as part of this RFP submission. \n \nThe successful Proponent will have a manager onsite that can immediately respond to a \ncustomer services issue. \n \nD. ACCESSIBILITY \n \nFor VAA, accessibility and inclusion are about making our airport Better for Everybody. \nWe believe everyone should have access in order to enjoy a barrier-free and accessible \ntravel experience and we continually work to promote inclusivity at Victoria International \nAirport. \n \nE. SECURITY \nThe successful Proponent, while not responsible for general security of the Parking Facilities, \nwill accept responsibility for all Revenues collected on behalf of the Authority and for \nincidents of property damage and injury that occur within areas of their responsibility. \n--- PAGE 9 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 8 \n \nF. HEALTH AND SAFETY  \n \n1. The successful Proponent shall comply with all Work Safe BC rules and regulations, \nOccupational Health and Safety rules and regulations, including but not limited to: \nmaintaining safe working conditions, provision of personal protective equipment, \nprovision of first aid personnel and supplies, investigation of accidents/incidents, \nmaintenance of records and statistics, instruction of workers and adequate training in \nthe safe operation of machinery and equipment. \n \n2. The successful Proponent shall maintain, at its own expense, an Occupational Health \nand Safety Program that complies with applicable health and safety legislation, Victoria \nAirport Authority’s health and safety requirements, and good industry practices. \n \nG. FINANCIAL RESPONSIBILITIES \n \n1. Revenue Collection \nThe successful proponent will be responsible for: \ni. Invoicing, collection and security of all Revenues and Sales Taxes related to \nthe Employee Parking (Employee and Airline Commuter parking). \nii. Invoicing, collection and security of all Revenue and Sales Taxes related to \nmonthly parking permits issued for Lot 1 or Lot 2. \niii. Collection and security of all Revenue and Sales Taxes collected from the \nshort-term parking lot. \niv. Collection and Security of all Revenue and Sales Taxes collected from Lot 1 \nand Lot 2 (daily parking lots). \nRevenue collected will be counted and reconciled in a secure location.  All Revenue \ncollected above under point I to iv will be deposited into the successful Proponent’s \nbank account no less that one time weekly.  All Revenues and Sales Taxes collected \nwill be forwarded to VAA no later than the 5th business day of the following month, \nalong with the operator’s required monthly accounting to VAA.  VAA will be \nresponsible for remitting any required Sales Taxes to the taxing authority. \n \n2. Monthly Accounting Report and Related Requirements \nThe successful Proponent will be responsible, no later than the 5th business day of \nthe month following, for providing a monthly reconciliation report by parking lot \nand Revenue type, in the required format, which may change from time to time that \nwill include: \ni. All Revenue and Sales Taxes collected directly by the successful Proponent, \nii. All credit card processing fees incurred by the successful Proponent, \niii. All Revenue and Sales Taxes deposited directly into VAA’s bank account, \n--- PAGE 10 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 9 \n \niv. All credit card processing fees incurred by VAA for revenues deposited \ndirectly into VAA's bank account. \nThe successful Proponent will also be responsible for providing to the Authority the \nfollowing financial reports: \n \ni. Weekly Statement of Account providing details of all Revenues earned \nrelated to the parking facilities by Revenue type and lot, \nii. Employee Shift Schedules and Hours of Work (upon request), \niii. List of current employees (monthly), \niv. Additional revenue or expense reports as specified by VAA, \nv. Details of any collection or invoicing challenges encountered related to the \ninvoicing for Employee Parking or Monthly Parking passes in Lot 1 or Lot 2. \n \n3. Financial Controls and Audits \nThe Authority reserves the right to audit the following at any time without prior \nnotification to or consent of the Contractor: \n \ni. Any and all staff records. \nii. All performance requirements. \niii. The level of customer service provided by the successful Proponent. \niv. Secondary audits of parking transactions and related Revenues. \nv. Onsite employee timesheet and payroll records. \n \nH. PARKING EQUIPMENT, FACILITIES  \n \nAll parking equipment and maintenance thereof related to the operation of the Parking \nFacilities will be provided by the Authority or their agent.  These will include: \n• All Parking Revenue Control equipment (PARCS) \n• Kiosks \n• Utilities \n• Lighting \n• Fixed and dynamic signage \n• Digital gantry sign (to be installed in spring 2025) \n• CCTV \nA list and description of the current PARCS equipment in use is attached as Appendix D.  \n \nThe building and equipment provided by the Authority will be used for the operation of the \nParking Facilities and related services and for no other purposes unless prior written \napproval is obtained from the Authority.  \n \n--- PAGE 11 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 10 \n \n  \nI. STATISICAL REPORTING \nVAA developed and currently manages its own statistical reporting for parking such as daily \noccupancy reports and passage reports. The successful Proponent will be required to \nassume responsibility for these reports either in the current format or in a proposed format \nacceptable to the Authority.  Daily and monthly reports are automatically sent from the \nSkidata Parking System to the Authority in a PDF format. \nSamples of the statistical reports are attached as Appendix E. \n \nJ. MARKETING \nThe successful Proponent will implement a robust marketing plan to optimize parking \nRevenue, utilization, and customer service.  The marketing initiatives could include internet-\nbased parking marketing techniques, including pre-paid reservations. All marketing must be \nin both official languages (English and French) and be pre-approved by the Authority. It is \nexpected that the Proponent would budget 0.5% of public parking Revenues toward \nMarketing. \n \nK. YYJ PARKING PERMIT PROGRAMS \n \nCurrently, VAA oversees its Air Terminal Building employee parking, commuter parking for \npilots and flight attendants, and monthly parking permit programs. Under the new Contract, \nVAA requires the Contractor to assume responsibility for managing these programs, \nincluding all financial aspects such as invoicing, payment processing, and the collection of \noutstanding fees. \n \nL. INNOVATION \n \nVAA values innovation as a key driver of operational excellence and encourages Proponents \nto continuously identify and present creative solutions, industry innovations, and emerging \ntrends that can enhance the parking experience, enhance Revenue opportunities and \noperational efficiency. Proponents are expected to proactively bring forward value-added \ninitiatives throughout the term of the agreement, leveraging advancements in technology, \nsustainable practices, and customer-centric approaches to deliver exceptional results. New \nservices may require infrastructure spending which will be borne by the Contractor and \ncharged back to the Airport Authority under business terms that are mutually agreed upon. \nExamples of new services could include Valet Services and Public Parking Shuttles. \n \nM. TRANSITION PLAN \nThe Proposal must include a comprehensive transition plan outlining how the Proponent \nintends to assume responsibility for operating the Parking Facilities. If the incumbent \n--- PAGE 12 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 11 \n \nContractor is the successful Proponent, the transition plan should address how they will \nimplement any new requirements outlined in this RFP that differ from their current \nContract. Any costs associated with establishing operations in the Parking Facilities will be \nthe sole responsibility of the successful Proponent and must not be passed on to the \nAuthority. \n1.7 EVALUATION CRITERIA \n \n The evaluation will be conducted by an evaluation committee made up of Authority employees   \nand its agents.  The Authority will evaluate all Proposals and look for overall value and most \nadvantageous Proposal.  The Authority is not to be limited as to its criteria for evaluation of \nProposals. Criteria will include, but is not limited to: \n \n• The Proponent’s ability to deliver and perform a quality service. \n• The Proponent's ability to demonstrate relevant experience, qualifications, company \nphilosophy, staff compensation programs, staff training programs, and evidence of \nsuccess providing parking and curb management services. \n• The Proponent’s financial plan including capital investment potential and profit sharing. \n• The Proponent’s reputation for quality service. \n• The Proponent’s experience managing similar parking and curb management programs. \n• The Proponent’s presence in the local markets and its ability to support the operations \nwith staffing, supervision, administration and technology. \n• The Proponent’s ability to recruit and retain staff through innovative and effective \nmethods will be a key consideration.  \n• Proponents should identify opportunities for Indigenous business engagement, skills \ntraining and employment in their Proposals.  \n• The Proponent’s capability and willingness to work in partnership with the Authority to \ndeliver and maintain exemplary parking services. \n• The Proponent’s financial stability. \n• The Proponent’s ability to demonstrate knowledge of safety standards as required by \nthe Canadian Centre for Occupational Health and Safety (CCOHS). \n• The Proponent’s references. \n• The quality of the Proposal. \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n--- PAGE 13 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 12 \n \n Weighting \nUnderstanding and Approach \nClear indication that the Proponent understand the scope of work and requirements and \nthat the Proposal is complete, easy to read, and flows well. \n \n25% \nDescription of how the Proponent will meet the requirements outlined in Section 1.6 of \nthis RFP \n25% \nFirst Nations Opportunities 5% \nPricing 30% \nOther Factors/Value Add 15% \n \n \n1.8 ONSITE PRESENTATION \n  \nAfter the Proposal due date, the Authority may require any Proponent, at the Proponent's cost, \nto make on onsite oral presentation.  Such presentation(s) will provide an opportunity for the \nProponent to clarify its Proposal to ensure a through and mutual understanding of its benefits.  \nProponents would be notified by email, and the onsite presentation would take place at the \nVictoria International Airport, 2\nnd floor of the Air Terminal Building (1640 Electra Blvd).  The \nAuthority may, following any such presentation(s) require that the information provided during \nsuch presentation(s) be confirmed in writing.  The written confirmation provided will then form \npart of the Proponent’s Proposal.  \n \n1.9 DEBRIEFING \n \nAt the conclusion of the RFP process, all Proponents will be notified.  Unsuccessful Proponents \nmay request a debriefing meeting within thirty (30) days of receiving notification.  This can be \narranged by contacting the Authority’s Authorised Representative. \n \n2.0 PROPOSAL INFORMATION \n2.1 ELIGIBILITY TO SUBMIT A PROPOSAL \n \nIn order to submit a Proposal, a Proponent must meet the following pre-qualification \nrequirements: \n \n• The Proponent or its master franchisor (including those third parties detailed under \nSection 2.15) shall have been in the parking management business for a minimum of \nfive (5) years immediately prior to June 1st, 2025. \n• The Proponent’s experience managing parking and curb management at a comparable \nor larger airport is desirable. \n \n \n \n \n--- PAGE 14 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 13 \n \n \n \n2.2 DEADLINE DATE AND TIME FOR RESPONSE TO RFP \n \nResponses to this RFP for Parking Management Services  are due  \nMonday, March 31\nst , 2025 no later than 2:00 pm Pacific Standard Time (PST). \n \n2.3 MANDATORY PRE-BID MEETING AND SITE TOUR \n \nA MANDATORY pre-bid meeting and site tour for companies intending to submit a Proposal in \nresponse to this RFP will take place on:  \n \nDate: Thursday, February 27\nth, 2025  \nTime: 1:30 pm PST \nPlace: Victoria International Airport- 2nd Floor Administration Office \n 201-1640 Electra Blvd, Sidney BC V8L 5V4 \n \nMeeting instructions will be provided once Schedule One - Receipt Confirmation/Intent to \nSubmit a Proposal/RSVP for Mandatory Pre-Bid Meeting and Site Tour has been submitted.   \n \n \nThe site tour requirements are as follows: \n• Valid government-issued photo ID for all visitors \n• CSA-certified High-visibility vests for all visitors \n• Flat footwear \nCompanies who do not attend the mandatory pre-bid site meeting and site tour will \nbe excluded from bidding on this RFP. \n \n \n2.4 ISSUING OFFICE / AUTHORITY’S REPRESENTATIVE \n \n Victoria Airport Authority \n 201-1640 Electra Blvd \nSidney, B.C. V8L 5V4 \n \nAttention:   David Parson, Commercial Development Officer \nPhone:  (250) 413.7897 \nEmail:  rfpparkingmgmt@yyj.ca\n \n \n \n2.5 INQUIRIES \n \nAll inquiries and other communications relating to this RFP and any subsequent agreements are \nto be directed in writing to the above named person only, who is the Authority’s Representative \nor his designate. \n--- PAGE 15 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 14 \n \nDepending on the nature of the inquiry, the Authority may respond to inquiries in writing or if \nappropriate, issue a written addendum to the RFP to all Proponents registered as having returned \ntheir RFP Receipt Confirmation Form. \n \nIt is the responsibility of each Proponent to inquire and clarify any requirements of this RFP which \nare not understood.   \n \nThe Authority shall have no responsibility for, and  the Proponent agrees not to rely upon \ncommunications, representations or statements regarding this RFP, its subject matter or any \nsubsequent agreements from any other persons other than the Authority’s Representative or his \ndesignate. \n \n2.6 PROPOSAL SUBMISSION DETAILS \n \nThe Proponent shall, before submitting its Proposal, thoroughly examine and assess the Proposal \ndocuments, the site, and the equipment and materials needed to carry out and perform the  \nservices.  The Proponent must also be knowledgeable of all relevant laws, rules, notices, \ndirectives, standards, orders and regulations, licensing and permit requirements, labo ur market, \nand other circumstances that may affect the Proposal. \n \nSubmission of a Proposal constitutes a representation by the Proponent that it is familiar with and \naccepts the foregoing. \n \nThe Proponent must submit one (1) original hard copy, and a digital copy on a USB stick \nof its completed Proposal including applicable appendices prior to  \nthe closing date and time to the attention of: \n \nDavid Parson – Commercial Development Officer \nVictoria Airport Authority \n201-1640 Electra Blvd. \n2\nnd Floor Administration Offices \nSidney, BC V8L 5V4 \n \nThe closing Date and Time is Monday , March 31st , 2025 no later than 2:00 pm Pacific Standard \nTime (PST). \n \nIt is the Proponent’s responsibility to ensure that their Proposal submission meets the deadline \nstipulated above, the time stamp by the administration office will be the official time received. \n \nThe Proponent’s Proposal must be signed by an authorized signatory of the Proponent.   \nThe Proponent must note on the outside envelope that the Proposal is for the Parking \nManagement Services at YYJ.  \n \nNo hand-written Proposals shall be accepted. \n \nProposals sent by facsimile or email will not be accepted; mis-delivered Proposals may not be  \n--- PAGE 16 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 15 \n \naccepted.  The Authority reserves the right to make additional copies of all or part of the \nProponent’s Proposal for internal use or for any other purpose required by law.  Proposals will \nNOT be publicly opened.  The Proponent will be advised of the results after the evaluation of all \nProposals received are complete. \n \nThe Authority reserves the right in its sole discretion, to extend the closing date prior to the closing \ndate and time and  will endeavor to notify the Proponent as soon as practically possible in the \nevent of any extension of the closing date. \n \nProposals received after the closing date and time will not be accepted. \n \n2.7 KEY TARGET DATES \n \nFollowing are the Key Target Dates and Events with respect to this RFP process.  Such dates are \nnot guaranteed and may change based on circumstances. \n \nA. Request for Proposals Issued February 13th, 2025  \nB. Receipt Confirmation Form due February 20th, 2025 2:00 pm PST \nC. RSVP for Pre-Bid Meeting and Site Tour February 20th, 2025 2:00 pm PST \nD. Pre-Bid Meeting and Site Tour (Mandatory) February 27th, 2025 1:30 pm PST \nE. Deadline for Questions March 6th, 2025 2:00 pm PST \nF. Question Response Deadline March 10th , 2025  \nG. Closing Date for Submission of Proposals March 31st, 2025 2:00 pm PST \nH. Award to Successful Proponent (if any) April 24th, 2025  \nI. Contract Commencement June 1st, 2025  \n              This schedule may be subject to change without liability to the Authority. \n \n2.8 PROPOSAL REQUIREMENTS \n \nProposals will remain  valid and open for acceptance by VAA for sixty (60) days following the \nclosing date.  \n \nSpecific detailed requirements are contained in each of the Schedules  attached to this RFP.  The \nProponent must include, but is not limited to the following ,within its Proposal: \n \n• Schedule One – Receipt Confirmation Form \nIn order to receive information regarding the mandatory pre-bid meeting and site tour, and \nany addenda or  other correspondence from the Authority in connection with this RFP , the \nProponent must complete and submit the Receipt Confirmation Form by email, courier, or \nhand delivery to the Authority by February 20\nth, 2025. \n \n• Schedule Two - Submission Checklist \nThis form is provided to assist the Proponent to ensure all Schedules have been submitted. \n \n \n--- PAGE 17 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 16 \n \n• Schedule Three - Company Profile \nThe Proponent must list its company information including officers, board of directors, \naffiliations, and/or partnerships contact information, address, telephone or cell phone \nnumbers and email addresses. \n \n \n• Schedule Four - Proposal Response Document \nIn order to evaluate all P roposals received, a standard response document is required.  To \nassist the Proponent in the submission, each section of the Proposal Response Document is \nlisted in Schedule Four along with the description of the content required.  Written responses \nare to be made in the same sequence indicated in Schedule Four using the same headings and \nnumbers. \n \n• Schedule Five -  Financial Proposal Form \nThe Financial Proposal Form is to be completed in its entirety and submitted in excel format. \n \n• Schedule Six - Proponent’s Declaration \nProponents must sign declaration. \n \n• Schedule Seven – Contact Information Form \nThe New Party Contact Information Form is to be completed and submitted as part of the \nProposal.  \n \n2.9 PROPOSAL COSTS \n  \nThis RFP does not obligate the  Authority to pay any costs the Proponent may incur in the \npreparation of their Proposal.  All costs  and expenses incurred by the Proponent  such as travel \nexpenses to YYJ by the Proponent for the purposes  of the mandatory pre -bid meeting and site \ntour, information gathering or presentations to VAA, will be at the sole cost of the Proponent. \n \nAll costs and expenses with respect to the submission of a Proposal pursuant to this RFP shall be \nthe sole responsibility of the Proponent and the Authority assumes no liability whatsoever for any \nProponent costs and expenses.    \n \n2.10 OWNERSHIP \n \n All Proposals and supporting material will become the property of VAA. \n \n2.11 WITHDRAWL OF PROPOSALS \n \nProposals may be withdrawn prior to the closing date and time only.  Withdrawal notification \nmust be in written form and may be attached to an email to the Authority’s Representative and \nreceived by VAA prior to the closing date and time. \n--- PAGE 18 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 17 \n \n2.12  ADDENDUM \n \nThe Authority may, at any time prior to the closing date and time, issue additional information, \nclarifications, or modifications to the RFP by written addenda issued by the Authority’s \nRepresentative or his/her designate only.   Any addenda shall be considered an integral part of \nRFP.  \n \nTo receive any addenda, the Proponent must complete and submit a copy of the completed \nAppendix A- RFP Receipt Confirmation Form to the Authority as set out therein.  \n \nThe Authority will post addenda to its website and will otherwise use reasonable efforts to notify \nProponents of any such addenda, but it is the Proponent’s sole responsibility to ensure receipt of \nall addenda before submitting their Proposal. \n \n \n2.13  OMMISSIONS AND DISCREPENCIES \n \nIf the Proponent is in doubt as to the meaning or interpretation of anything in the RFP, find any \ndiscrepancies in, or find omissions from the RFP, the Proponent should immed iately contact the \nAuthority’s Representative. \n \nThe Proponent shall be solely responsible for any error, omissions, discrepancies or \nmisunderstandings resulting from the Proponent’s failure to examine thoroughly the RFP and \nfrom the Proponent’s failure to enquire further with the Authority. \n \n2.14 INTERPRETATION \n \nNo oral interpretation of this RFP by anyone, whether or not employed by the Authority, shall be \neffective to alter or modify any of the provisions in the RFP. \n \nEvery request for interpretation of the meaning of any of the requirements of the RFP shall be \nmade in writing to the Authority’s Representative only. \n \n \n2.15 PARTNERING / STRATEGIC ALLIANCES / SUBCONTRACTING \n  \nThe Proponent may partner with other third parties in order to fulfill all of the requirements set \nout in this RFP, provided that all partners, joint venturers and the like: \n• sign the signatory page of the Proposal,  \n• provide similar company profiles for each organization,  and any other documents as may, \nfrom time to time, be required by the Authority. \nProposals that include partnerships must include how the partnership will function within the \ndelivery of the services. \n \n--- PAGE 19 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 18 \n \nThe use of a sub -contractor, who must be clearly identified, to provide a portion of the \nProponent’s service or product is acceptable.  This includes a joint submission of two or more \nfirms having no formal corporate links.  In either case, one Proponent must be prepared to assume \nprimary responsibility for successful delivery of the scope of work described and for statutory \nobligations under the Worker’s Compensation Act, etc.  This must be clearly defined in the \nProposal. \n \n2.16 NO COLLUSION \n \nExcept as specified within its Proposal, the Proponent declares that no other person, either \nnatural or corporate, has or will have any interest or share, directly or indirectly, in this Proposal \nor in the proposed Contract, which may be awarded.  By submitting a Proposal, the Proponent \nwarrants that there is no collusion or arrangement, formal or informal, between the Proponent \nand any other actual or prospective Proponent in connection with its Proposal submitted for this \nRFP; the Proponent has no knowledge of the contents of any other Proposal; and the Proponent \nhas made no comparison of figures, agreement or arrangement, express or implied, with any \nother party in connection with the making of its Proposal, except as declared within the Proposal. \n \n2.17 DISCLOSURE OF INTEREST \n \n The Proponent is required to fully disclose in its Proposal: \n \na) Any relationship the Proponent may have with any employee, officer or director of the \nAuthority; and \nb) The nature of that relationship. \nFailure to disclose, or false or insufficient disclosure of the nature and extent of the relationship \nthe Proponent may have with an employee, officer or director of the Authority shall be grounds \nfor termination of any Contract with the Authority in the A uthority’s sole discretion without \nfurther liability or notice. \n \n2.18 RESERVED RIGHTS OF THE AUTHORITY \n \nThe Authority reserves the right to request clarifications and/or additional information as is \nnecessary to properly evaluate a  Proposal, negotiate with any Proponent or with another \nProponent or Proponents concurrently.  The Authority is not required to offer any modified terms \nto other Proponents. The Authority shall incur no liability to any Respondents as a result of such \nnegotiations or modifications. \n \nThe Authority reserves the right to cancel this RFP, to reject any or all Proposals; to re -advertise \nfor Proposals if necessary; to waive minor irregularities and formalities; and to accept the Proposal \nwhich offers, in the Authority’s sole judgement, the best overall value for the Authority.  All \nexpenses incurred by the Proponents will be solely at its own cost. \n \nThis RFP does not constitute an offer.  No Contract shall result upon submission of Proposals.  The \nAuthority is not under obligation to enter into a Contract with anyone in connection with this RFP \n--- PAGE 20 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 19 \n \nor responses received, nor pay for any costs incurred in the preparation of P roposals submitted \nin response to this RFP. \n \nThe Authority will consider past performance of the Proponent on other agreements in terms of \nquality of work and compliance with terms and conditions of those agreements.  The Authority \nmay also utilize other available resources to determine the Proponent’s record of past \nperformance. \n \n2.19 WAIVER OF NON-COMPLIANCE \n \nProposals which contain qualifying conditions or otherwise fail to conform to the instructions may \nbe disqualified or rejected.  The Authority may, however, in its sole discretion, retain, for its \nconsideration, evaluation and potential award, Proposals which are non-conforming because they \ndo not contain the content or form required by the instructions in this RFP or because the Proposal \ndoes not comply with the process for submission set out in the instructions in this RFP. \n \n2.20 CONFIDENTIALITY \n \nNotwithstanding anything contained herein, the Proponent agrees that  it will not exploit  any \ninformation, whether delivered to the Proponent by the Authority, or whether retrieved by the \nProponent by any other means and will make no direct or indirect disclosure to any other party \nof said information without the prior, express written agreement of the Authority. \n \n2.21 APPLICABLE LAW \n \nThe laws and courts of British Columbia shall apply and have exclusive jurisdiction over this RFP \nand any subsequent Contract which may be awarded. \n \n2.22 NO LIABILITY \n \nBy submitting a Proposal, the Proponent agrees that in no event will the Proponent claim damages \nfor any amount whatsoever for any cost incurred by the Proponent in preparing its Proposal or \nfor matters relating to any agreement or matters concerning the competitive pr ocess, and, the \nProponent, by submitting a Proposal, waives any claim for loss of profits if no Contract is made \nwith the Proponent. \n \nAny information contained in this RFP and attachments is provided to assist the Proponent in the \npreparation and submission of its Proposal.  The Authority assumes no responsibility for the use \nof this information for any other purpose. \n2.23 CONSENT TO INVESTIGATION \n \nIn order to allow the Authority to properly determine the qualifications and capabilities of a \nProponent, the Authority reserves the right in its sole discretion to conduct such investigations of \na Proponent’s business experience, financial capability and business practices as it deems \nnecessary, and the Proponent agrees to permit and cooperate with such investigations. \n \n--- PAGE 21 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 20 \n \n2.24 ALTERING DOCUMENTS \n \nProponents must not electronically alter any portion of this RFP with the exception of adding the \ninformation requested.  To do so, will invalidate the Proponent’s Proposal or response. \n \n2.25 DISCLAIMER \n \nWhile precautions have been taken to ensure that this file will not interfere with or cause damage \nto your system or its existing data, the Authority accepts no responsibility for damages that may \nbe caused by this file and makes no other warranty or representation, either expressed or implied \nwith respect to this file.  This file is provided “as is” and you, as the user,  assume the entire risk \nwhen you use it. \n \n2.26 WAIVER \n \nDue to the vag aries of electronic transmissions, the Authority does not guarantee, nor will it be \nliable for the accuracy of what is read or what is downloaded in this file. \n \n \n3.0 CONTRACT INFORMATION \n \n3.1 AWARD OF CONTRACT \n \nThe Contract resulting from this RFP, if any,  will be awarded in accordance with the process set \nout in Section 1.7 of this RPF- Evaluation Criteria. \n \n3.2 FORM OF CONTRACT \n \nThe successful Proponent will be required to enter into a Parking Management Services Contract \nwith the Authority in a form su bstantially similar to the form of Contract attached to this RFP at \nAppendix H (the “Contract”).  The Authority reserves the right to negotiate, modify, and/or add \nany contract terms and conditions to the Contract. \n \nProponents are encouraged to familiarize themselves with the content of the Contract and not in \ntheir Proposals any objections  to the terms and conditions or any items to be discussed or \nnegotiated.  The Proponent must satisfy itself in all respects as to the risks and obligations to be \nundertaken under any Contract entered into, as a result of the RFP. \n \nAll or part of this RFP and all or part of the Proposal may be incorporated into and form an integral \npart of the Contract. \n \n \n3.3 CONTRACT NEGOTIATIONS \n  \nThe Authority intends to negotiate and conclude a Contract with the most qualified and \nresponsible Proponent offering the best overall value, quality, and most advantageous Proposal. \n--- PAGE 22 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 21 \n \n \nA Contract must be concluded with the Authority based on the proposed (or negotiated) Proposal \nno later than thirty (30) business days from the official notification by the Authority of award to \nthe successful Proponent or the rights and privileges of this  opportunity may be forfeited unless \notherwise agreed to in writing by the Authority. \n \nIn the event a Proponent and the Authority fail to reach an agreement , negotiations may be \nterminated by the Authority , without any compensation whatsoever payable to the Proponent.  \nAn alternate Proponent may then be invited to  participate in the negotiation process.  This \nprocess may be repeated as often as necessary. \n \n3.4 REJECT AND RE-NEGOTIATE \n \n The Authority may reject all Proposals received and re-advertise for Proposals if necessary.  Such  \n cancellation of the RFP process does not preclude the Authority from subsequently meeting with \n any Proponent to negotiate a Contract that best suits the needs of the Authority. \n \n3.5 NO CONTRACTURAL OBLIGATION  \n \nThe Authority shall not be obligated in any manner to any Proponent whatsoever until a written \nContract has been negotiated and duly executed related to any Authority accepted Proposal. \n \n3.6 CONTRACT OFFER \n \nA Contract offer for Parking Management Services will only be made in writing by the Authority’s \nPresident and CEO. \n \n3.7 REQUIRED COMPLIANCE \n \nThe Proponent with whom the Authority chooses to enter into a Contract, if any, must comply \nwith all federal, provincial, and local laws, regulations, requirements and orders applicable to the \nperformance of any Contract which may result from this RFP process, including but not limited to, \nand Federal, Provincial, or Municipal occupational health and safety regulations or codes, \nelectrical and building codes, Work Safe BC regulations , and rules and regulations of any \ngovernment entities that have jurisdiction.  \n \n3.8 EXCLUSIVITY \n  \nThe Authority will not enter into an exclusive Contract with any successful Proponent during the \nterm of the Contract.  At any time, the Authority may at its discretion enter into other Contracts \nfor services similar to those of the successful Proponent.  It is understood and agreed t hat the \nAuthority will discuss any plans with the existing successful Proponent but cannot grant the right \nto any exclusivity to any individual successful Proponent. \n \n \n \n--- PAGE 23 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 22 \n \n3.9 PERMITS \n \nThe successful Proponent will be responsible to obtain and maintain all permits, licenses, and \napprovals required by Federal, Provincial, and Municipal or other government agencies to enable \nit to operate at the Airport. \n \n \n3.10 HOURS OF OPERATION \n \nThe Authority will require the successful Proponents to provide continuous service to the \ntravelling public by staffing the Parking Facilities on a full-time basis, with their hours of operations \nsufficient to provide service for all arriving and departing  flights. Sample flight schedules can be \nreviewed in Appendix G. \n \nThe Air Terminal Building is currently closed between 01:00 am and 03:30 am. \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n \n--- PAGE 24 ---\n VICTORIA AIRPORT AUTHORITY - REQUEST FOR PROPOSALS \n 2025 PARKING MANAGEMENT SERVICES \n  \n  \nPage | 23 \n \n \n \nSCHEDULE ONE \nRECEIPT CONFIRMATION FORM/INTENT TO SUBMIT A PROPOSAL \nRSPVP FOR MANDATORY PRE-BID MEETING AND SITE TOUR \n \nProponents intending to submit a Proposal in response to this Request for Proposal must complete this \nform and return it no later than February 20th, 2025, to receive any further distributed information \nabout this Request for Proposal.   \n \nMANDATORY PRE-BID MEETING AND SITE TOUR: Further to Section 2.3 of this RFP, please submit \nnames and email addresses of your company representatives who will be attending the mandatory pre-\nbid meeting and site tour, which will take place at YYJ on Thursday, February 27th. 2025 at 1:30 pm. \n \nSubmission of this form does not bind the Proponent in any way. Please 